<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The first session of the 10th Supreme People's
Assembly of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
Saturday amended and supplemented the constitution and elected a
new state leadership. (DPRK-Constitution Revision)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- The Bangladeshi government will set up environmental
courts to try violators of laws on environment protection,
Environment and Forest Minister Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has already approved a draft proposal which has
been sent to the Law Ministry for vetting and taking measures in
this regard, she said at a discussion on "Environmental Law in
Business," organized by the Bangladesh Environmental Lawyers
Association. (Bangladesh-Environment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwaiti parliamentary delegation will
address again the world water crisis at the 100th
Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU) conference due to begin in Moscow
on Monday, the Kuwait News Agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will present an interjection regarding measures
to secure water preservation and remove obstacles preventing human
beings from finding necessary water resources, the news agency
said. (Kuwait-IPU-Proposal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Five Iranian hostages released by the Afghan Taliban
militia returned to Tehran via Islamabad, Pakistan, on Sunday,
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Three of the five were taken hostage in August while two
others were captured last year by the Taliban and imprisoned in
Qandahar, southern Afghanistan, the news agency said.
(Iran-Taliban-Hostage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia -- Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk said
Sunday that he will ask to abdicate if he could not resolve the
current political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 75-year-old monarch made the statement at a working meeting
he hosted in his Siem Reap residence. (Cambodia-King-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi has rejected a proposal
made by the United States and Britain that two Libyans suspected
of blowing up a Pan Am flight be tried in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering in Tripoli late Saturday, Gaddafi said
that this is not the trial in a third country that Libya has
demanded but a deal "to make the third country a transit point to
transfer the accused to Britain."  (Libya-Lockerbie-Rejection)
</P>
</TEXT>
