<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Party Launches New Logo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's biggest
opposition party, the National Party (NP), launched new colors
and a new policy package Sunday for next year's general
elections.
</P>
<P>
The new logo, unveiled after being approved by the NP's
national caucus Saturday, consists of a golden sun on a green and
blue background, representing the "new life force and dynamism"
of the party.
</P>
<P>
It replaces the yellow and red sun logo adopted by the party
in the run-up to the 1994 elections in an effort to change its
image.
</P>
<P>
The caucus Saturday also agreed to relaunch the party with a
four-point election plan.
</P>
<P>
The NP's move came two days after the release of an opinion
poll conducted in July, which showed the support for NP had
dropped to an all-time low of nine percent and its position as
the number one opposition party was under threat.
</P>
<P>
Launching the new logo Sunday, NP leader Marthinus van
Schalkwyk said the move was part of a process of "dramatic
modernization" in the party.
</P>
<P>
He said the new policy document, which will be debated and
fleshed out at the party's provincial congresses later,
emphasizes the concepts of inclusive government and "localism".
</P>
<P>
But he dismissed the idea that the NP was considering
returning to the government of national unity. He said what the
party wanted was a system of multi-party government, in which
major parties could serve on the executive and not be muzzled.
</P>
<P>
Localism involved a radical devolution of power and funds to
local government level, van Schalkwyk said. Local communities,
rather than national government, should make decisions on
schools, policing, welfare and health centers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The party also called for restructuring the National Council
of Provinces, upper house of the South African parliament, to
include not only provincial and local interests, but cultural
groups, traditional leaders and business and trade unions.
</P>
<P>
The policy document, which used the phrase "new National
Party" prominently, introduced a slogan: "Let's get South Africa
working." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Congress Opts to Lead Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- In a significant policy
change, India's biggest opposition party decided on Sunday to keep
its option open to lead a coalition government instead of forming
an alternative administration on its own.
</P>
<P>
However, coalitions would be considered only when absolutely
necessary, the Congress party said in an 11-page declaration
adopted at the end of a three-day brainstorming session in
Panchmarhi, a hill resort in central Madhya Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
In view of opposition from its own ranks, the Congress party
said, arrangement should be made on the basis of agreed programs
which did not compromise its basic ideology, the Press Trust of
India reported.
</P>
<P>
The party considered the present difficulty in forming a
one-party government a transient phase in the evolution of its
policy, said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The declaration laid to rest speculation that Congress will not
go for coalition with other parties.
</P>
<P>
It noted with serious concern the weakening of the party in
some states including Uttar Pradesh, Bihar and Tamil Nadu, and
decided to accord highest priority to its revival and renewal in
these states.
</P>
<P>
"In the interim, coalitions may well be needed," Congress
President Sonia Gandhi said in her concluding address. But she
also reiterated that she would not shirk from putting together an
alternative government to succeed the government led by the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) if it collapses.
</P>
<P>
She explained that the politics of coalition at the national
level was a "passing phase." "We will come back again with full
force and on our own steam."
</P>
<P>
Congress also adopted an eight-point program which includes a
campaign from next Thursday to collect 10 million signatures to
press for the implementation of recommendations by the Srikrishna
Commission which probed the "communal" riots in Mumbai in 1993.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Sonia Gandhi told the opening of the conclave that
Congress was ready to form an alternative government in the event
of the fall of the government. "If and when the need arises, our
party will fulfill its constitutional obligation without
hesitation and provide stability and progress."
</P>
<P>
She mounted a scathing attack on the government for its
"all-round failure," saying the economy was stagnant, inflation
was on the rise, investment was at an all-time low and foreign
policy was in tatters as the ruling coalition partners remained
embroiled in squabbles.
</P>
<P>
The Congress meeting took place against the backdrop of
repeated offers of support to Congress by several non-BJP parties
including Rashtriya Loktantrik Morcha and the Communist Party of
India (Marxism) in taking the initiative to pull down the
government led by Atal Bihari Vajpayee and form an alternative
administration on the basis of a common minimum program.
</P>
<P>
Sonia Gandhi said the constituents of the coalition were
engaged in an internecine war, bringing to the fore contradictions
among them day after day, as they spoke in different voices on
national and international issues.
</P>
<P>
The Congress leader also attacked what she termed as "confused
and unclear" foreign policy of the Vajpayee government towards
China and Pakistan, adding that it also made no effort to mend
ties with India's traditional allies who opposed its nuclear tests
in May.
</P>
<P>
"Peace with our neighbors is an essential prerequisite. But in
a matter of a few weeks, the present coalition government
destroyed what the Congress had painstakingly achieved over a
10-year period to normalize our relations with China," said Sonia
Gandhi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
