<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Ministers Clear Ban on Yugoslav Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union foreign
ministers Sunday cleared the way for an agreed ban on Yugoslav
flights to come into force.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers, meeting in Salzburg of Austria, removed
Greek objections to the ban on flights by Yugoslav carriers to and
from EU member states which agreed in principle in June to ban
Yugoslav flights, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The paperwork for the flight ban is expected to be completed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers also raised the possibility of
tightening the existing sanctions against the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia unless Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ends the
fighting by security forces in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that both Milosevic and ethnic Albanian
militants have to end hostilities in Kosovo for any effort to work
to bring peace back to the region.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union saw the ban on Yugoslav flights as a
punishment for Belgrade over its policy on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The union earlier suspended all new investment in Serbia to
force Belgrade to end its forceful action in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
