<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Prices Relatively Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) said on Monday that the average price
of its basket of seven crudes stood at 11.99 U.S. dollars a barrel
last week, slightly less then the 12.04 dollars quoted a week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The average crude oil price last month was 11.89 dollars per
barrel, slightly less than July's average of 12.05 dollars, but
still far less than last year's annual average of 18.68 dollars
and the benchmark price of 21 dollars per barrel set by OPEC.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC group is composed of Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and the
United Arab Emirates. It is estimated that OPEC members possess 75
percent of the world's known reserves of crude oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Find More Ways to Make a Good Living </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Eighty percent of the
young farmers in a remote village at Dingzhou, a city in north
China's Hebei Province, have left their hometown to take new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 of the 1,000 villages are working on contracted
building projects in foreign countries such as Singapore, Japan
and the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
This is just one case of villagers leaving home to open their
own businesses. At present 60 million farmers, 13 percent of China's
rural laborers, are working in urban areas in various sectors of
industry, commerce and catering, said an official from China's
Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
When many villagers leave their hometown to find opportunities,
those who still stay in the rural areas develop farming, the
service trade and rural industries.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers in the Dingxi Prefecture in northwest China's
Gansu Province, once "the most seriously poverty-stricken area" in
China, took advantage of their mules to run tourist services. A
large number of tourists are attracted to the prefecture by its
numerous canyons, and they can earn 1,000 yuan from each mule
every year.
</P>
<P>
Farmers also choose to work at rural businesses. By the end of
1997, the rural industry had absorbed 1.42 million rural laborers,
accounting for more than half of the surplus laborers in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
Xie Baisan, a professor from Fudan University, said that
farmers in China have changed their ideas about how to get
affluent by freeing themselves from farmland and pursuing a
variety of professions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  Russian Duma Again Rejects Chernomyrdin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma again
rejected Viktor Chernomyrdin's nomination as prime minister on
Monday, despite earlier efforts to break the political stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Only 138 deputies at the lower house of parliament voted for
Chernomyrdin, who was renamed premier August 24 after five months
in the political wilderness, way below the required simple
majority of 226 votes. Two hundred and seventy-three deputies
voted against with one abstention.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear when the third, or final, vote will take
place. Under the Russian constitution, if the nomination is
rejected three times, the president will have to either select a
new candidate or dissolve the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges More Aid to Developing Nations  (Embargoed for Tuesday) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday attached great importance to the development in
the world at large and called for more external aid to developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the appeal in his annual report to the 52nd session
of the General Assembly, which is scheduled to conclude on Tuesday
after adopting the report.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge of development remains paramount in a world
where one fifth of humanity is forced to fend for itself on a
meager dollar a day," he said.
</P>
<P>
Citing short life expectancy and poor illiteracy in some
developing countries, Annan said, "one third of all Africans are
not expected to survive past the age of 40, nearly 40 percent of
women in developing countries are illiterate."
</P>
<P>
"More than half of South Asia's children remain underweight at
age five, while on-going Asian economic crisis may thrust some 50
million people in Indonesia alone back into poverty," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the volume of external aid to developing
countries "has declined steadily throughout this decade, and now
stands at 0.22 percent of the GDP of the industrialized countries
-- only 0.19 percent for the group of seven major industrialized
countries, which includes the richest among them," said the U.N.
chief.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, donor countries are increasingly earmarking aid, with
no guarantee that their aid-giving preferences match the need of
the recipients, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign direct investment has not compensated for this decline
in aid; in 1997 all of sub-Saharan Africa received a mere 3
billion U.S. dollars, and South Asia 4 billion U.S. dollars," he
said, adding that "many developing countries, including some of
the poorest, remain subject to the crushing burdens of external
debt."
</P>
<P>
Since he assumed office last year, Annan, the first U.N.
secretary-general from the sub-Saharan Africa, has hammered out a
reform program which includes underlining the importance of
development on the U.N. agenda.
</P>
<P>
"My program of reform begun over the course of the past year
builds on this institutional capacity, has already yielded
practical results in the developing area," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 52nd session of the General Assembly will be followed by
the 53rd session which kicks off on Wednesday, one week earlier
than the past regular sessions, which usually begins on the third
Tuesday in September every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
