<HEADLINE> HKSAR Govt Stands Firm on Introducing LPG Taxis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government's position on LPG
(liquefied petroleum gas) taxis has not changed, the Planning,
Environment and Lands Bureau said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In response to a report by local Chinese-language press Monday
that the LPG taxi scheme may be aborted, a spokesman of the Bureau
 reiterated that the government remains firmly committed to
improving air quality and wishes to introduce LPG taxis as an
essential and effective measure to abate vehicular air pollution.
</P>
<P>
"Only a substantial reduction of diesel vehicles by replacing
them with a clean alternative fuel will bring sufficient
improvements to our air quality to safeguard public health," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that LPG vehicle technology has proven to be a clean
alternative and is readily available, subject to the provision of
supporting infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government had received very useful feedback from an
ongoing one-year LPG taxi trial launched last November and was
using it to develop a clean air motor fuel strategy, he said. The
trial aims at ascertaining the reliability of LPG vehicles under
local intensive driving environment and providing necessary cost
information on fuel consumption and repair and maintenance
requirements.
</P>
<P>
"The government intends to consult the relevant trades and the
public soon on the implementation strategy. Given the health
benefits of using LPG, we are confident that this initiative will
find favor with the trades and the community," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
