<HEADLINE> Vogts Resigns as German Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Berti Vogts has resigned as
German national coach, the German Football Federation (DFB)
announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vogts made the decision to go following a telephone
conversation with German federation (DFB) president Egidius Braun.
</P>
<P>
The 51-year-old has been under fire since Germany's 3-0
quarter-final loss to Croatia in the World Cup this summer. The
criticism sharpened after his side's performances in last week's
friendlies, which saw a 2-1 win over Malta and a 1-1 draw with
Romania.
</P>
<P>
A DFB statement said a successor would be found as soon as
possible with Germany's opening Euro 2000 match against Turkey
just a month away.
</P>
<P>
Vogts replaced Franz Beckenbauer as national chief after
Germany's 1990 World Cup triumph. 
</P>
</TEXT>
