<HEADLINE> Egypt's Crude Production Down by 2.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt produced 2.6 percent less
crude oil in 1997/98 fiscal year than the year before, an annual
report by the Egyptian General Petroleum Corporation released on
Monday said.
</P>
<P>
Crude production for 1997/98 fiscal year (ending June 30)
totaled 40.7 million tonnes compared to 41.783 million tonnes the
year before.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas production, according to the report, was up by 3
percent to 13.244 million tonnes in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
Crude treated in local refineries amounted to 29.442 million
tonnes in 1997/98 compared to 28.273 million in 1996/97.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local consumption of oil products and natural gas
increased by 9.1 percent to 33.753 million tonnes this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite a series of new oil discoveries, Egypt decided to cut
down its oil output since July 1 by 20,000 barrels per day to
830,000 barrels in a move to help stabilize the nose-diving
international oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas sector accounts for about one-fourth of the foreign
currency income of Egypt, which is not a member of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
