<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists: No Obvious Rise or Drop in Global Sea Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists claim that
global sea level will not experience an obvious rise or drop in
the next century, causing no threat to human civilization.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zichu, a famous Chinese glaciology expert attending the
ongoing Sixth International Symposium on Antarctic Glaciology in
this capital of northwest China's Gansu Province, said that the
scientific discovery challenged a popular point in world
scientific circles that warming of the world climate will result
in a rise in the global sea level.
</P>
<P>
Xie, also an academician of the International European-Asian
Academy of Sciences, said the warming will also cause a decline in
the sea level of almost the same amount, virtually canceling out
the effect of the rise.
</P>
<P>
"The change of sea level will be minor and not obvious," the
expert said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many scientists worldwide agree that the
temperature on the Earth's surface is rising owing to the
influence of atmospheric warming, which also leads to increased
melting of glaciers.
</P>
<P>
The melted water will obviously increase the sea level,
according to some foreign scientists, who predicted more than
three million cubic kilometers of glacial water will be added to
the oceans, raising the level by 5-to-6 meters in the next 100
years.
</P>
<P>
Scientists warned of a great influence on social development
and economic construction in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
But global warming also will cause a drop in the sea level,
according to Xie and Han Jiankang, another Chinese scientist in
the field.
</P>
<P>
Based on their long-term research and reliable statistics on
the subject, Xie and Han submitted evidence that climate warming
will increase evaporation from the oceans.
</P>
<P>
The water will turn into more rainfall in the areas of the
North Pole and South Pole, enlarging and thickening the ice
sheets, they said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the thickening of the glaciers in the
South Pole area over the past 40 years is much more than the
amount of melting and breaking apart of the ice sheets in the same
period, they said.
</P>
<P>
The margin between melting and thickening will result in a
dropping of the sea level, Xie said, "However, this will not add
more land to coastal countries because a Sino-Russia math system
on global water change indicates that the procedure will be very
slow."
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 trillion tons of glaciers would form in South
Pole area if global temperatures rise about five degrees Celsius,
Xie said. "This would cause a dropping of the sea level, but occur
about 30,000 years later," he said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the sea level dropped by 30-to-50 centimeters over
the previous 100 years, counteracting the rise caused by the
melting of glaciers, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0029 </DOCNO>
