<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Re-opens to Navigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Navigation on the Yangtze River,
which had been blocked by floods for 43 days, fully resumed today.
</P>
<P>
On July 26, the Chinese government issued an order to ban
navigation on the river in an effort to ensure the security of the
dikes.
</P>
<P>
As the water level receded, the State Flood Control
Headquarters decided to re-open the navigation route on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
By 8 p.m. today, the five warning lines in the banned areas had
been removed, and 1,238 ships that were affected by the order have
been allowed to proceed.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the navigation authorities said that all work has
returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
This was the longest time that ships were banned from sailing
on the Yangtze, the longest river in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Currency Depositors in Singapore Urged to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Banks in
Singapore (ABIS) Monday urged all holders of Malaysian currency to
contact their banks to settle the status of their ringgit deposits
by Tuesday so as to meet the September 9 deadline set by the
Malaysian government.
</P>
<P>
Under the newly-introduced rules, Malaysia will not recognize
funds of its currency of ringgit held by non-Malaysians outside
Malaysia after September 9, 1998, the ABIS said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ABIS noted each bank in Singapore adopted its own approach
to minimize the impact to ringgit depositors as much as possible
and most banks offered extended business hours and hot-line
numbers to help customers with ringgit accounts.
</P>
<P>
All banks have agreed to allow their ringgit depositors to
convert their ringgit deposits into foreign currency at the
request of the depositors, the ABIS added.
</P>
<P>
The ABIS affirmed that many banks have decided to institute an
"auto convert" system to convert depositors' ringgit accounts into
another currency before September 9 and some others are
considering an automatic conversion if they can not contact the
depositors in time.
</P>
<P>
In all cases, the best advice is for customers to contact their
banks before the deadline so that arrangements could be made, the
ABIS stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the ABIS, local banks are seeking to ensure that
customers' interests are protected in some ways. They are helping
customers to pre-terminate their ringgit fixed deposits before
ringgit deposits outside Malaysia are no longer recognized by
Malaysia and the conversion is conducted at a spot rate of four
Malaysian ringgits to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Asset Management Ltd. of the United
Overseas Bank, one of the four biggest banks in Singapore,
announced in the evening its decision to suspend trading of the
United Malaysia Fund with immediate effect, saying "the imposition
of exchange control measures, announced by the government of
Malaysia on September 1, 1998, has made it impractical for UOB
Asset Management Ltd. to continue operating its United Malaysia
Fund as an open-ended unit trust fund."
</P>
<P>
The UOB Asset Management Ltd. said it will issue a statement in
the next seven days to inform unit-holders of the next course of
actions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
