<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trying to Eliminate Leprosy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China aims to reduce the rate
of leprosy to less than 0.1 per 10,000 in 95 percent of counties
and cities by 2000 and reach that standard in all the counties and
cities by 2010, an official from the Ministry of Health said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Yin Dakui, vice minister of health, told the 15th International
Leprosy Congress which opened here today, that more than 490,000
leprosy patients have been detected in China from 1949 to 1997,
and 4,045 patients need treatment at present.
</P>
<P>
The national average rate has been lowered from 2.4 per 10,000
in 1966 to 0.033 per 10,000, according to Yin.
</P>
<P>
He said leprosy has a history of more than 2,000 years in
China, and was regarded as incurable. The disease not only caused
disabilities but also social fears and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government pays great attention to controlling the
disease and has worked out regulations and plans regarding its
control in past decades. A national supervision and detection
system and a leprosy data bank have been established in China,
according to Yin.
</P>
<P>
He added that leprosy patients are treated free of charge in
China. The country has more than 1,200 hospitals and clinics
employing 5,700 professional doctors specializing in leprosy.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, an effective measure to prevent the disease
has not been found. Every year, about 2,000 new patients are
detected in China, mainly in remote and poor regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has 120,000 persons disabled and handicapped
by the disease. "They need care and help from the society," said
Yin.
</P>
<P>
China will strengthen its leprosy education programs to let
people know the disease is curable and reducing discrimination
toward sufferers of the disease, said Yin.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government also provides life subsistence to
persons affected by leprosy, and tries to offer more employment
opportunities to persons who have recovered from the disease, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
