<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unearthed Skulls in Qinghai Show Signs of Skull Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Unearthed skulls in the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau show that craniotomy was performed by
Chinese early in the Neolithic Age 5,000 years ago, according to a
Chinese archeologist.
</P>
<P>
Han Kangxin, an archeologist of Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said that the latest research shows craniotomy appeared
in the Majiayao culture period (about 4,000 to 5,500 years
ago). Archeologists found that the crack in some skulls healed
very well after the operation. Craniotomy is the surgical opening
of the skull, usually for operations on the brain.
</P>
<P>
Traces of craniotomy have also been found on unearthed skulls
of the Kayue culture period (2,000-to-3,000 years ago), which
proves that the operation was used in ancient Qinghai for about
3,000 years, Han said.
</P>
<P>
Modern brain operations grew out of the ancient craniotomy, he
said, adding that craniotomy found on the unearthed skulls in
Qinghai is the earliest in China.
</P>
<P>
According to the Qinghai Archeology Institute, the remains of
the Majiayao culture was distributed in Gansu and Qinghai
provinces in the Neolithic Age and the remains of the Kayue was
that of a bronze culture in the eastern part of Qinghai Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
