<HEADLINE> Govt Planes Bomb Rebel-held Towns in East Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Congolese rebel leader
Earnest Wamba Dia Wamba Monday accused government planes of
bombing two rebel-held towns in east Congo (K), a report reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
"Government planes coming from Kindu bombed Kalemie and Lubutu
and we are protesting the fact that they are now targeting
civilian populations," Wamba said in his headquarters of Goma.
</P>
<P>
Wamba said the bombs had missed their target in Kalemie, about
500 kilometers south of Goma, falling into Lake Tanganyika. But
he did not say anything about casualties or damages in Lubutu, a
village about 360 kilometers west of Goma, a town bordering
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The bombings happened at a time when peace talks were being
held at Victoria Falls grouping a rebel team with Congolese
President Laurent Kabila and leaders of neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Wamba said the summit would grant the rebels recognition from
regional leaders and allow them to present their case.
</P>
<P>
"Just being there at the summit is already a recognition by
the heads of state attending the meeting, and we will use this
recognition to present our case forcefully," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, composed of a mixture of opposition politicians
and disgruntled soldiers allegedly backed by neighboring Rwanda,
accuse Kabila of bad governance, corruption and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
"We can't let this government continue and we appeal to all to
understand that we have a just case to fight for. We are fighting
against dictatorship and for democracy."
</P>
<P>
Kabila's forces, backed by Angola and Zimbabwe have repulsed
the rebel assault to the west of Kinshasa and have stepped up the
pressure in the rebel's eastern stronghold.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the warring sides in Congo, presidents of Zimbabwe,
Namibia, Angola, Uganda, Rwanda, Mozambique, and Zambia along
with Organization of African Unity chief Salim Ahmed Salim are in
session at Victoria Falls, a northwestern town of Zimbabwe trying
to hammer out a cease-fire in the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers of Banyamulenge, or Congolese Tutsis took up arms on
August 2 in east Congo to topple President Kabila. 
</P>
