<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Plans Huge Investment for Industry Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- This economic and financial
center of China will invest 260 billion yuan in industrial
restructuring and upgrading in 1998-2000 to keep economic growth
on the fast track.
</P>
<P>
The planned investment, which is 100 billion yuan more than the
figure for the 1995-1997 period, is expected to ensure that
Shanghai's industrial output value will grow an average of
12-to-13 percent each year, to 700 billion yuan by the year 2000,
according to Vice Mayor Jiang Yiren.
</P>
<P>
"The effort to increase industrial investment is meant to
expand domestic demand, create more jobs and help to ensure a high
growth rate for the national economy," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qifan, director of the Municipal Economic Commission,
said that after years of economic restructuring since the 1980s,
Shanghai has formed six pillar industries: automobiles,
telecommunications equipment, complete power stations or plants,
petrochemicals, iron and steel, and household electrical
appliances.
</P>
<P>
Last year the pillars accounted for 52 percent of Shanghai's
industrial output value and 55.4 percent of industrial gross
profits, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of hi-tech industries -- such as those
in micro-electronics and computers, modern biology and medicine,
and new materials -- accounted for 15 percent of the city's
industrial output value last year.
</P>
<P>
"With the rise of the pillar and hi-tech industries, Shanghai's
industrial structure is becoming less and less resources-based and
more and more technology- and capital-intensive," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The three years between 1998 and 2000 is a critical period for
Shanghai to complete the transformation process, he added.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Shanghai will step up its effort to expedite the
industrialization of high technologies, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
"We're striving for an average annual growth rate of 25-to-30
percent for the hi-tech industries of information, modern biology
and medicine, and new materials," he said. "The combined output
value of these industries will reach 142.8 billion yuan by 2000,
or more than 20 percent of our total industrial output value by
then."
</P>
<P>
He said that Shanghai will also take measures to expand the
application of new and high technology to the pillar industries to
raise their output value to 314.4 billion yuan by 2000, which
represents an annualized growth rate of 11-to-14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to the development of medium- and
hi-grade cars, air-conditioned buses, environmental protection
equipment, digital household electrical appliances and multi-media
large-screen color TV sets, according to Huang.
</P>
<P>
He also said that greater efforts will be made to develop such
sectors as clothing, foodstuffs, packaging design, printing and
publishing, computer software and fitness equipment to maintain
the average growth rate at 8 percent each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
