<HEADLINE> Turkey: Turkish-Israeli Security Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said Monday that Turkey's growing military ties with Israel
should not be seen as a threat to other countries.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz made the remark during a welcoming ceremony hosted in
his honor by his Israeli counterpart Benjamin Netanyahu after
Yilmaz arrived here from Jordan for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the strength of our ties (with Israel) will serve
not only the interests of our respective countries, but also peace
and stability in this region," Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's speech was apparently aimed at addressing the concern
of other countries in the region, particularly Syria, Egypt and
Greece, about the Turkish-Israeli security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have been developing strategic ties since
1996, exchanging warplanes for training, conducting naval
maneuvers and signing several defense and trade deals.
</P>
<P>
Israel army radio reported that during his visit, Yilmaz is
seeking an Israeli promise of military assistance in case of war
between Turkey and Greece in their dispute over control of
Cyprus. But Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai denied this
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops landed and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a pro-Athens coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that the real dimensions of Turkish-Israeli
relationship are well understood. Turkish-Israeli cooperation is
not against any other country," Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
For this issue, Netanyahu said "it is a cooperation barred
to none."
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, the two prime ministers started their
talks inside the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz will also discuss the Middle East peace with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in the West Bank city of Ramallah
on Tuesday before his departure for Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
