<HEADLINE> S. Korea Ranks Second Lowest In Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea ranked next to last
among nine Asian nations during the first half of this year in
economic growth and import increase, the Bank of Korea said Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea registered a minus 3.8 percent year-on-year growth
in gross domestic product (GDP) in the first quarter of the year,
second only to Indonesia's minus 7.9 percent, said the central
bank in a report comparing the economies of the nine Asian
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The comparable economic growth rate of Hong Kong stood at minus
2 percent in the first three months of this year, followed by
Malaysia's minus 1.8 percent and Japan's minus 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In imports, South Korea saw a plunge of 36.1 percent, second
only to Indonesia's 36.4 percent in the first quarter of the year,
while Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore and Japan registered negative
growth of 35.3 percent, 21 percent, 20.5 percent, and 17.7 percent
respectively in imports.
</P>
<P>
In term of currency appreciation, the South Korean won grew
stronger by 2.2 percent the first half of the year, just after
Thailand's currency appreciated 11.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, Japan, Malaysia and Indonesia saw their currencies
depreciate 2.4 percent, 6.0 percent, 6.3 percent, and 63.9 percent
respectively in the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
