<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Leprosy Conference Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 cured Chinese
and foreign leprosy sufferers are attending the 15th International
Leprosy Congress, which opened in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
They will participate in the six-day conference as equal
partners with more than 1,000 scientists from 67 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin wrote a greeting for the conference:
"Eradicate Leprosy for the Benefit of Mankind."
</P>
<P>
"Leprosy, a disease with a sinister potential to devastate the
entire lives of affected persons without actually killing them, is
a reflection of the extreme under-development which still persists
in many parts of the world," said Dr. S.K. Noordeen, senior
adviser of the World Health Organization's Action Program for the
Elimination of Leprosy.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible today to fight the disease successfully," he
said. "It is a relatively weak enemy -- taking years to evolve,
and is only feebly infectious, and today it is highly amenable to
treatment."
</P>
<P>
Leprosy is not merely a health issue, he said, but also a human
rights issue. "Generations of leprosy-affected men and women have
been exposed to cruel stigma and ostracism, and I sincerely hope
that we shall put an end to that injustice once and for all," he
said.
</P>
<P>
China has no longer taken leprosy as a seriously infectious
disease, and has canceled leprosy's listing on the health
declaration card for people entering China, said Yin Dakui,
vice-minister of health.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-seven cured foreign leprosy sufferers have come to
China to attend the conference. Leprosy-affected people, who no
longer were infectious, have also come to China as tourists.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the congress is "Working Toward A World without
Leprosy," said Dr. Yo Yuasa, President of the International
Leprosy Association (ILA). He said that a large number of medical
professionals have worked to reduce the prevalent rate of leprosy
during the past century since the first international leprosy
congress was held in Berlin in 1897.
</P>
<P>
"The congress will try to explore the medical and social
aspects of the disease, both of which need a solid basis of
science and humanity," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of 1998, the number of registered leprosy
cases for treatment in the world was 828,000, most of which were
concentrated in 16 countries in the Asian, African and American
continents.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence of leprosy in China is 0.033 per 10,000, and
there are currently more than 4,000 leprosy patients who have
registered for treatment across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
