<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand to Hold Joint Trade Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar trade delegation, led
by Minister of Commerce Major General Kyaw Than, left here Monday
for Thailand to attend the first meeting of the two countries'
Joint Trade Commission, Radio Myanmar reported Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which is to begin in Bangkok Thursday,
will be chaired by Kyaw Than and Thai Deputy Prime Minister and
Commerce Minister Supachai Panithapakdi.
</P>
<P>
Border trade issues and investment are expected to top the
agenda of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kyaw Than will also attend the opening ceremony of the Bangkok
Gems Fair due to begin Wednesday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Last December, foreign ministers of Myanmar and Thailand agreed
at the 4th meeting of Myanmar-Thai Joint Commission for Bilateral
Cooperation in Bangkok to enhance their bilateral cooperation in a
number of sectors including trade.
</P>
<P>
According to Myanmar official statistics, bilateral trade
including border trade stood at 330 million U.S. dollars in the
1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, up from 289 million
dollars in 1996-97. The balance of trade was in Thailand's favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
