<HEADLINE> Seoul Hopes For Improved Inter-Korean Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea voiced renewed hope
Monday that the new leadership of the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) would open an era of peace and cooperation in
inter-Korean relations.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the newly elected DPRK leadership, the
Unification Ministry said Monday the DPRK, as a responsible member
of the international community, should make sincere efforts to
contribute to peace on the Korean Peninsula and the Northeast
Asian region.
</P>
<P>
"We hope inter-Korean dialogue will resume as soon as possible
so that the 1991 basic agreement (signed by Seoul and Pyongyang)
and the 1994 Geneva nuclear framework (signed by Pyongyang and
Washington) can be faithfully implemented," said the ministry in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Kim Jong-il was re-elected chairman of DPRK's
National Defense Commission, the highest military supervisory body
of the country, at a session of the Supreme People's Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The assembly also picked a new cabinet with Hong Song-nam as
premier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
