<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Enterprises Reports Satisfactory Interim Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Enterprises Holdings
Limited, the investment arm of the Beijing Municipal Government in
Hong Kong, Monday reported a 24-percent increase of profit in the
first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The red-chip company announced in its interim report that its
operating profit attributable to shareholders in the first six
months amounted to 249 million HK dollars (32 million U.S.
dollars), up 24 percent from the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Earnings per share were approximately 0.4 HK dollars (five
U.S. cents). The board of directors proposed an interim dividend
of 0.1 HK dollars (1.2 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
Listed in Hong Kong in mid-1997, the conglomerate has built up
its presence in production of consumer goods, infrastructure,
technology industry, tourism and related services in Beijing,
capital of China.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhaoguang, chairman of Beijing Enterprises, told a press
conference Monday that brewery and manufacturing of telephone
switching systems contributed heavily to the satisfactory profit
growth in the first half.
</P>
<P>
An airport expressway owned by the company reported a slight
increase in earnings, but its tourism, hotel and retail
subsidiaries suffered from the Asia financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Interest income of 80 million HK dollars (10 million U.S.
dollars) from unused initial public offering proceeds made part
of the interim profit.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that the company's financial position remains
strong, with a 17-percent debt-to-equity ratio.
</P>
<P>
Looking into the future, Hu said that the company will continue
to tap the potential of the existing businesses, and at the same
time, explore new growth points in the high-technology sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
