<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Issue 10 Billion in State Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Monday announced that it will issue state bonds worth 13.9
trillion won (10.3 billion U.S. dollars) for institutional and
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
The funds raised by the bonds will provide unemployment
benefits, flood damage restoration, overhead costs and the
recently revised supplementary budget, said the Ministry of
Economy and Finance Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bonds are scheduled to go on sale Tuesday and be available
until the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Bonds valued at five trillion won will be issued this month,
4.7 trillion won in October, 3.4 trillion won in November, and
eight trillion won in December.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be sold through 95 underwriters, including banks
and insurance companies. The ministry will decide on the coupon
rates based on prevailing market rates.
</P>
<P>
Beginning Tuesday, the public will be able to buy government
bonds at security firms, investment trust companies, merchant
banks and insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
However, the volume of bonds available to the public, analysts
said, may not be enough because banks and security firms are
likely to resell most of their new bond holdings to investment
trust companies.
</P>
<P>
Investment trust companies may not offer the state bonds to the
public since they usually acquire bonds as a part of a pool of
various securities, including stocks and corporate debentures, say
analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
