<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New U.N. Project to Support Poverty-Alleviation in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) will provide 1 million U.S. dollars in
grants for a new joint project with the Chinese government to
support the UNDP-funded poverty-alleviation programs in China.
</P>
<P>
The project, to be completed in 2000, is aimed at improving
the implementation of the ongoing and future UNDP
poverty-alleviation projects in China, according to a document
signed early this week.
</P>
<P>
A special coordinating office consisting of a technical
advisory board and an oversight panel, and a results-oriented
monitoring and evaluation mechanism and a management information
system for micro-finance will be developed under the project to
ensure the quality and quantity of UNDP's poverty-alleviation
operations in China.
</P>
<P>
A series of managerial and technical training sessions will
also be provided to such relevant personnel as project staff
members and farmers.
</P>
<P>
To date, UNDP has been supporting 17 poverty alleviation
related projects covering 58 impoverished countries in north and
west China, with the total aid in grants exceeding 21 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
