<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Windows 98 Well Received in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents in China's major
cities have reacted positively to the Chinese version of Windows
98, Microsoft's latest personal computer operating system.
</P>
<P>
Minutes starting at midnight of Sept. 1, six proprietary shops
in Shanghai, Beijing, Guangzhou, Fuzhou, capital of east Fujian
Province, and Chengdu, capital of southwest Sichuan Province, sold
333 copies of the Chinese version of Windows 98, which was ushered
into China on Aug. 31. The average sales of 55.5 copies per shop
is very close to the average sales of 57 copies when the English
version was unveiled in the United States more than two months ago,
</P>
<P>
The symbolically successful initial sales indicate that, after
20 years of market economy reforms, China now has a computer
software consumer group who closely follow the latest global
developments in the field, a Shanghai-based Microsoft official
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many of China's major PC makers -- including Legend,
Founder and others -- have cooperated with Microsoft to market PCs
with preinstalled Chinese versions of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China had more than 10 million
PCs and more than five million users of Microsoft's Windows
software.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, which has a population of 13 million, some 1.5
million residents participated in computer training programs in
the last five years.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources say that Windows 98 offers more and better
network functions than Windows 95, which was introduced in China
in 1996, as well as better integration of work and recreational
functions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
