<HEADLINE> U.N. Development Program Helps Laid-Off Women Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and the Chinese government have jointly launched a
four-year project to promote employment for laid-off women workers
in China's urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to contribute to job creation and
re-employment for laid-off women workers by means of employment
information and consultation networks, stronger training capacity
and new-venture creation services.
</P>
<P>
The project, to be carried out in Tianjin initially, will
assist the All-China Women's Federation (ACWF) and Tianjin Women's
Federation (TWF) to improve their contributions to re-employment,
self-employment and venture creation in Tianjin, where nearly 60
percent of the city's 320,000 laid-off workers are women.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a system of regular collection and analysis
of relevant information and a computer information system for the
TWF Employment Information Center will be established to provide
an employment information network in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The project also intends to increase the fund-raising capacity
of Tianjin and the ACWF through various forms of networking.
</P>
<P>
The total financial input for the project will be 1.04 million
U.S. dollars, with 740,000 U.S. dollars from the UNDP in grants
and 300,000 U.S. dollars from the Chinese government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
