<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Surplus Increases in first 7 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a
significant increase in its trade surplus in the first seven
months of this year as a result of a higher growth in exports over
imports.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus amounted to 26.2 billion ringgit (6.894
billion U.S. dollars) during the period under review against a
deficit of 3.6 billion ringgit (947.368 million U.S. dollars) in
the same period last year, according to the Statistics Department
which released Monthly External Trade Statistics here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed the seven-month surplus to the 40.8
percent increase in exports to 162.7 billion ringgit (42.815
billion U.S. dollars) from 115.6 billion ringgit (30.421 billion
U.S. dollars) in the corresponding period in 1997 while imports
rose 14.6 percent to 136.5 billion ringgit (25.921 billion U.S.
dollars) from 119.1 billion ringgit (31.342 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The department said electrical and electronic products
persisted as Malaysia's largest export earner, netting receipts
amounting to 84 billion ringgit (22.105 billion U.S. dollars) or
sharing 51.7 percent of total export earnings during January-July
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
Palm oil and palm-based products retained their position as the
second largest export revenue earner during the first seven months
of 1998, with a total combined value of 12.3 billion ringgit
(3.236 billion U.S. dollars), or sharing 7.6 percent of total
exports.
</P>
<P>
Other major export revenue earners included liquefied natural
gas (LNG) which accounted for 3.0 percent of total exports, and
crude petroleum, ranking as the fourth largest export earner and
comprising 2.8 percent of total exports.
</P>
<P>
Turning to imports, the department said that the major
categories of imports by end-use for the current period were
intermediate goods, sharing 69.5 percent of total imports, capital
goods 17.1 percent and consumption goods 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
For July alone, the ninth consecutive month to record a surplus
since November last year, the surplus was at 4.1 billion ringgit
(1.078 billion U.S. dollars), which was lower by 2 billion ringgit
(526.315 million U.S. dollars) from the previous month, the
department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
