<HEADLINE> Myanmar Cooperatives' Products Gain Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The products of Myanmar
cooperatives are gaining markets at home especially with its
import substitute goods.
</P>
<P>
Except high-technology goods, almost all merchandises including
household and personal goods are being produced by the
cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
Regional products are available from the country's 14 states
and divisions covering Kachin, Kayah, Kayin, Chin, Sagaing,
Tanintharyi, Bago, Yangon, Magway, Mon, Shan, Mandalay, Rakhine
and Ayeyawaddy.
</P>
<P>
Among the regional products are marbles, sculptures, medicinal
plants, silver, bronze and lacquer wares, silk and cotton, dried
shrimps, fish and prawn, foodstuff and leather.
</P>
<P>
Export items of the cooperatives include jade and jewelry,
beans and pulses, rubber and wood products,
</P>
<P>
Their exports earned 19.6 million U.S. dollars in 1997-98
fiscal year which ended in March, 133,000 dollars more than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar cooperatives took part in different trade fairs in
South Korea, Israel, Indonesia and the Philippines in recent
years, finding markets for its products.
</P>
<P>
The cooperatives are also seeking joint ventures with foreign
firms or individuals to expand business.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 21,700 cooperative societies in Myanmar,
owning over 630 factories out of 51,738 in the country.
</P>
<P>
The cooperative sector contributed 2.1 percent to the gross
domestic product, making up 2.3 percent in volume in the trade
sector, according to official statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
