<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Generate Power From Sea Waves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government
plans to generate power through the use of sea waves, according to
Technology Ministry sources Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the government will launch a project to
generate power from sea waves at Rumassala in Galle city in the
deep south of the country which will be completed within an year.
</P>
<P>
The entire cost of the project is estimated at about 100,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
By year 2008, Sri Lanka's total foreign exchange earnings from
tea, rubber and coconut will have to be spent on importing oil
unless alternative local energy resources are harnessed, the
sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Although there are several potential energy resources, they
said, most of them remain untapped. The sea waves project is a
contingency measure to tide over an impending power crisis.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the power plant comes in the wake of
successful experiments conducted by the Faculty of Engineering of
the University of Peradeniya, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
