<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Marks 24th Victory Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano, accompanied by leaders of the state government and
political parties, laid a wreath at the Monument to the People's
Heroes here to mark the 24th Victory Day Monday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech after the ceremony, Chissano called on all
Mozambicans to carry out the behest of the fallen heroes, and
work hard to rebuild the country, following the examples set by
those combatants fighting for the national independence.
</P>
<P>
Victory Day falls on September 7 each year when 24 years ago,
the Mozambique Liberation Front (Frelimo) signed a Lusaka
agreement with Lisbon on granting independence to Mozambique on
June 25, 1975.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the ruling Frelimo in a message to
the whole nation Monday urged all political forces and
organizations to cherish the national unity and the ideal of
independence and freedom.
</P>
<P>
It called on all Mozambicans to take an active part in
promoting the development of both urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The central committee also urged the government departments to
take effective measures to help rehabilitate women socially and
economically and support helpless children and old people.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Veterans for the National Liberation also
asked their members to set good examples for the younger
generations in loving peace, preserving national solidarity and
upholding freedom and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Victory Day was also celebrated in other parts of the country,
with songs and dances, sports games and fora. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mordechai: Israel Not to Take Hostile Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai said here Monday that Israel will not take
any hostile policy towards Cyprus because the relations between
the two countries are friendly.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with visiting European
Union's peace envoy to the Middle East Miguel Moratinos,
Mordechai said that Israel will never interfere into the affairs
of Cyprus and side with Turkey against Greece over the missile
issue in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has signed a deal with Russia to buy S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles, triggering a new round of tension on the divided
island. Turkey has threatened to use all means to block the
deployment of missiles.
</P>
<P>
Commenting the visit to Israel by Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz, Mordechai denied the Turkish Prime Minister's visit
is to seek Israel's support in the event of hostelity with
Greece over the station of missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said the missile issue in Cyprus is a sensitive one
and Israel has no intention to get itself involved.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz arrived here Monday morning for a two-day visit and
he is scheduled to hold talks with his Israeli counterpart
Benjamin Netanyahu and other Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
Beside other issues, the security cooperation between Israel
and Turkey would dominate the talks between the two prime
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos is here to help push the peace process forward
and he is scheduled to hold talks with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat in Ramallah later Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
