<HEADLINE> Multi-National Force to Be Deployed Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A multi-national force
comprising armed force and police will soon be deployed along the
border areas of Nigeria, Chad and Niger to combat the growing
menace of armed bandits, according to a military official.
</P>
<P>
The New Nigerian newspaper Monday quoted Colonel Mohammed
Bawa, military administrator of Gombe state, as saying that the
three neighbors had decided to form the multi-national force
because of the frequent cases of armed robbery on their borders.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Bawa assured local people in border areas that with
the deployment of the multi-national force, the problem of armed
banditry would be "a thing of the past."
</P>
<P>
The military administrator noted that the state anti-banditry
squad would be strengthened with necessary equipment to enable it
to carry out its duties effectively.
</P>
<P>
Last month, defense and foreign ministers of the three
countries held a meeting in Nigerian capital Abuja to discuss the
security situation along their common borders.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of the meeting said that a
joint committee had been set up to combat criminal activities in
Lake Chad area where rebels, bandits and other undesirable
elements had posed a serious threat to peace, security and
stability in the border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
