<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Sharply Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
staged its second biggest rise this year, with investors
optimistic because of expectations that the U.S. central bank may
be considering a rate cut and because of stronger Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index gained 65.2 points, or 2.6
percent, to 2,569.2 after trading within a range of 2,504.0 to
2,569.2 during the day.
</P>
<P>
It is the largest one day gain since August 19, when the index
added 2.75 percent, and the third biggest gain in a year after a
jump of 6.25 percent in October last year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also gave support to the share market,
ending a little stronger at 59.36 U.S. cents, up from 59.06 U.S.
cents locally last Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the equities markets, the all resources index stacked on
3.69 percent, or 35.7 points, to 1,002.1 with bargain hunters
hoping the recent dive in commodity prices had bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
Diversified miner BHP added 31.4 cents to 13.20 Australian
dollars, global miner Rio Tinto jumped 70 cents to 18.40
Australian dollars ahead of its first half results to be released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gold also added significantly to its recent gains with the
sector up 58.8 points, or 6.30 percent, to leave the gold index at
992.0.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index soared 104.1 points, or 2.36 percent,
to 4,512.3, led by the banking sector, whose index rose 145.6
points to 5,565.5 points on the back of interest rate speculation
and the hope it may soon be cheaper to borrow funds.
</P>
<P>
Home lending leaders Westpac bank added 35 cents to 9.35
Australian dollars and Commonwealth Bank of Australia stacked on
61.6 cents to 19.95 Australian dollars, while National Australia
Bank shares jumped 47 cents to 21.42 Australian dollars and the
ANZ bank was 25 cents firmer at 8.80 Australian dollars .
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 270.2 million shares worth 474.21 million
U.S. dollars with rises outnumbering falls 682 to 384. Steady
trades numbered 327. 
</P>
</TEXT>
