<HEADLINE> Pak Expresses Concern over Iran-Afghan Border Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Defense Committee of the
Cabinet of Pakistan Monday expressed the hope that the growing
tensions along the Afghanistan-Iran border will subside soon and
urged both countries to show the utmost restraint, an official
press release said.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the
Defense Committee called upon Iran and Afghanistan to take
necessary steps to calm the situation, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions are arising in Central Asia as Iran held military
exercises near its border with Afghanistan and announced it would
take any necessary actions if the Taliban did not free the 11
Iranian nationals.
</P>
<P>
The committee reviewed the Durban summit of the Non-Aligned
Movement, expressing satisfaction that South African President
Nelson Mandela, as chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement, has
invited the attention of the Movement to the need for an early
settlement of the long standing Jammu and Kashmir issue, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The committee noted that the official level meetings between
Pakistan and India at Durban have been useful in preparing the
ground for the meeting between the prime ministers of Pakistan and
India to be held in New York later this month, it said.
</P>
<P>
On Pakistan's signing of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, the
committee reiterated that a decision would be taken only in
supreme national interest and not under coercion of sanctions or
economic pressures, it added. 
</P>
