<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Firmer on U.S. Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
stronger Monday as speculation mounted over the prospect of an
official interest rate cut by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
Comments made by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan last Friday in the
U.S. were interpreted by markets as indicating the central bank
might be prepared to cut rates in the face of the turmoil in Asian
and South American markets.
</P>
<P>
As result, the U.S. dollar Monday lost ground against the
Japanese yen during Asian trading.
</P>
<P>
And the Australian dollar, which has been moving in line with
the Japanese yen recently, rose alongside its Asian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
"Weakness for the U.S. (dollar) will help the Aussie," said a
foreign exchange expert.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility that the lower rates out of the U.S. will
shore up emerging markets, takes a bit of pressure off commodities
(exporting nations such as Australia), (is) more good news for the
Aussie," he added.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended the day in Sydney at 59.36 U.S. cents,
up from 59.06 U.S. cents locally last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The strength of the Australian dollar Monday also was in part
due to firmer gold price. Gold closed in Sydney at 288.05 U.S.
dollars an ounce, up from 285.55 U.S. dollars last Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates the Australian dollar was at 78.37 Japanese
yen from Friday's close of 79.75 yen and 1.0236 German marks from
1.0238 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
