<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Rebel Leaders Join Peace Talks With Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Congo (K) rebel leaders
arrived at Victoria Falls Monday for talks with President Laurent
Kabila on ending civil war in the former Zaire, a report from the
Zimbabwean town reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready for talks, but there will no cease-fire without
a political settlement," said Arthur Z'ahidi Ngoma, deputy
President of the Congolese Democratic Coalition, when arriving
for a peace summit at Victoria Falls in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to talk. We have come to listen to the leaders
here, but we are not going to talk about a cease-fire before we
have a political settlement," Ngoma said, in reply to a question
about what the rebels' negotiating position is.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and the other key players in the Congo crisis,
President Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and President Pasteur
Bizimungu of Rwanda, arrived at Victoria Falls Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rebel team has come to northwest Zimbabwe to attend a
summit despite expressing discomfort with the venue and the
chairmanship of Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe, whom they say
has become an active participant in the war by deploying 2,800
troops to prop up embattled Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Also due to arrive Monday were Angolan President Jose Eduardo
Dos Santos, whose dispatch of troops to the Congo River corridor
has played a key role in reversing rebel gains, and Namibian
President Sam Nujoma, who is also supplying military logistical
help to Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Two neutral players, Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano and
his Zambian counterpart Frederick Chiluba, are also expected at
the summit along with Organization of African Unity (OAU)
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim and a special envoy of U.N.
chief Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders are in session seeking to iron out an
Africa peace formula that will lead to a cease-fire followed by
political negotiations and the formation of a broad-based
government in Congo (K), Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe began the peace initiative Sunday by conducting
bilateral consultations with Kabila, Museveni, Bizimungu and
Salim aimed at narrowing the differences between the main
parties.
</P>
<P>
Defense ministers and security chiefs from Kabila's allies --
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe -- held parallel talks to chart out
a military position to be presented to their bosses ahead of the
summit.
</P>
<P>
While a cease-fire and negotiations may be very difficult to
agree upon, observers here say the stumbling blocks to peace
might be the peace keeping operation required and how to finance
it.
</P>
<P>
They say a peace-keeping force would need 20,000 troops and
more. The only country with the logistical capability and
resources to payroll such an operation would be Pretoria, but
President Nelson Mandela has already expressed his reservations
about military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had been at odds with Mugabe over Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia's military involvement in Congo till last Thursday when
he made a sudden policy u-turn.
</P>
<P>
He said he "understood" why the troika countries had
intervened only after a regional meeting on the Congo crisis held
on the fringes of a Non-Aligned Movement summit in Durban, South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said he hoped this mini-summit would help bring peace
to Democratic Congo, saying, "we have to work toward democracy in
Congo because the lack of democracy is the source of this
problem."
</P>
<P>
Kabila accuses former allies Rwanda and Uganda of sending
troops to back soldiers of Banyamulenge, or Congolese ethnic
Tutsi community, who took up arms against Kabila in the east of
Congo on August 2.
</P>
<P>
But Uganda and Rwanda deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
The rebels made rapid gains in the east and west until Angola,
Zimbabwe and Namibia sent their troops to back Kabila's army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Surge on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices surged up on
Singapore Stock Market Monday reversing the continuous nosedive
trend in the past seven trading days.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) shot up 57.06 points to
end at 862.10 points as firmer currencies and stronger regional
stock markets lifted up market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed part of the surge to the start of futures
trading on the Morgan Stanley Capital International (MSCI)
Singapore stock index.
</P>
<P>
Other positive factors coincided with the start of futures
trading to give shares a hefty boost, they said.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover increased to 222.62 million units worth 241.79
million Singapore dollars (139.65 million U.S. dollars). Advancers
outstripped losers by 260 to 20 with 306 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
KepLand was the most active stock of the day with a volume of
13.67 million stocks traded. It was followed by IPC that had 13.27
million units done. DBS Land was next with 12.25 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 was the top gainer of the day as it gained 1.40
dollars to close at 18.50 Singapore dollars. SIA F rose 85 cents
to finish at 8.00 Singapore Dollars. SIA went up 52 cents to end
at 5.50 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
GP Bat w00 was the biggest loser of the day as it shed 15 cents
to finish at 0.65 Singapore dollars. PacCent moved down 13 cents
to close at 0.85 Singapore dollars. Noel inched down 10 cents to
end at 0.20 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
