<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Rally 8 percent on Government Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks soared
nearly 8 percent to close above the 8,000-point level on Monday on
a seven-point government package to strengthen the Hong Kong
dollar's peg to the greenback and to improve liquidity in the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
The key barometer Hang Seng Index jumped 588.29 points, or 7.86
percent, to close at 8,076.76 with across-the-board increases seen
in the four sub-sectors.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the seven technical measures, put forward by
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) Saturday, seemed to be
very positive in reducing the volatility of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
After opening at 3.00-3.50 percent from Friday's close of
4.00-6.00 percent, overnight interbank rate stayed at around 4.5
percent for most of the day, while the rates for one month, three
months and six months all fell significantly to the single-digit
level.
</P>
<P>
Lower interest rates, together with a firmer Japanese yen,
triggered the strong upward movement in the stock and futures
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index went up some 450 points in the first 15
minutes of trading Monday and gained 566.03 points, or 7.56
percent, to finish morning trade at 8,054.50.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng September futures soared 725 points to end at 7,895
points while October futures jumped 805 points to close at 7,800.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, red chips and H shares continued their upward trend
Monday, soaring over 10 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Market turnover rose to 9,762 million HK dollars (1,252 million
U.S. dollars), against Friday's 6,851 million HK dollars (878
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang on
Monday announced a 30-point plan to tighten up market discipline
and restore order in the securities and futures markets.
</P>
<P>
Tsang told a Legislative Council financial affairs panel
meeting that the program, together with the seven technical
measures announced at the weekend to strengthen the peg mechanism,
formed a comprehensive plan to improve the stability of Hong
Kong's monetary and financial systems to withstand cross-market
manipulation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
