<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Tests Distinguish Blood Relations Among Lesser Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Three-year-old lesser panda
Xiaoguai did not know until today that an uncle who had often
fought for food against her is her biological father
</P>
<P>
A DNA fingerprint test made by Chinese scientists, first of
its kind in the world for lesser pandas, proved Xiaoguai and her
father's blood relationship.
</P>
<P>
Another eight lesser panda cubs also found their fathers via
the DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say this finding is of great importance for
avoiding inbreeding in a group of lesser pandas.
</P>
<P>
This research program, after passing appraisal by experts,
helped established family histories for 22 lesser pandas in the
Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding Center.
</P>
<P>
China started began DNA fingerprint tests for giant pandas in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Lesser pandas, who enjoy the same state protection as giant
pandas, reside mainly in mountainous and forest areas in southwest
China's Sichuan, Tibet and Yunnan provinces, as well as in few
other countries.
</P>
<P>
The number of bamboo-eating lesser pandas has been reduced by
nearly 40 percent since the 1950s because of human expansion into
their natural habitats.
</P>
<P>
To protect these endangered wild animal species, China has
strengthened its breeding of captive lesser pandas. A
630-square-meter lesser-panda farm has been built within the
Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding Center.
</P>
<P>
It now 22 lesser pandas, and four females have given birth to
14 cubs since 1995. Nine of these have survived.
</P>
<P>
Senior zoologist Li Guanghan said the average life expectancy
of the lesser pandas is about 13 years, and they reach adulthood
by the age of two.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paul Ince Faces Wrath of FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Paul Ince may be banned from
competitive internationals for six months after being sent off
against Sweden in Stockholm last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ince will be automatically suspended from England's next match,
the European Championships qualifier against Bulgaria on October
10,
but could face further disciplinary action from both the Football
Association (FA) and Europe's governing body UEFA.
</P>
<P>
After being dismissed for a second bookable offence, Ince
tried to
have words with Henrik Larsson, the victim of his foul, then
verbally
abused the referee Pierluigi Collina. He was ushered away by
teammates but still had time to flick a V-sign in the direction of
the England bench and Swedish supporters behind it before
disappearing down the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
It was the 30-year-old former England captain's first sending
off,
but 12th and 13th bookings, in his 44-match international
career. He
became the sixth England player to be dismissed in 126 years, and
the
second in as many matches since the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The FA intends to wait to see if Collina, or the match
observer,
mention Ince's behaviour in their reports to UEFA before
commenting,
but there is already a grondswell of opinion in favour of taking
action independent of UEFA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaves for Silk Road Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel Monday departed from Ankara Airport for a high-level
conference on enhancing Asia-Europe links to be held in Baku,
capital of Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Local Daily News reported that the two-day conference is
expected to outline the necessary working ground for the
establishment of vital transportation links from Europe via the
Caucasus to Asia.
</P>
<P>
The conference called "Silk Road" in reference to the ancient
corridor linking Asia with Europe, is expected to end with the
signing of an agreement, which will express the readiness of the
participants for the construction of highways, railways and
waterways to connect Europe with Caucasus and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The development of these transportation links is seen as vital
with respect to the improvement of commercial and cultural ties
among nations in the region. The agreement to be signed will be a
basis for the participating countries to harmonize their legal
regulations regarding transportation and customs.
</P>
<P>
Demirel will deliver a speech at the conference and is also
expected to have face-to-face talks with other regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
High-ranking representatives of more than 30 countries,
including presidents, prime ministers and foreign ministers, are
expected to take part in the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
