<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Presents Photo Album of World War II in Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese professor has
donated a photo album taken by a Japanese soldier during World War
II to the Museum of Nanjing Massacre Victims, providing new
evidence of crimes committed against China by Japanese invaders in
the late 1930s.
</P>
<P>
The album was donated by Professor Yoshihiko Yamamoto of
Shizuoka University last month during his visit in Nanjing,
capital of Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The album contains 130 photos of battle scenes in a dozen
Chinese cities including Dalian, Changxindian, Shanghai, Suzhou,
Zhenjiang, Nanjing, Anqing, Jiujiang and Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
Most of the photos are marked with an exact date and place. The
earliest one was taken on July 29, 1937, soon after the July 7
Incident of 1937.
</P>
<P>
The burned bodies of Chinese victims of the Nanjing Massacre
are shown in four photos taken in Dr. Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum and
Xiaguan Port in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The album also includes five military maps. On one, titled "My
Victory," the Japanese soldier marked his army's invasion route
with a red line, passing through the seven Chinese provinces of
Liaoning, Hebei, Shanghai, Jiangsu, Anhui, Hubei and Hunan.
</P>
<P>
Yamamoto said that he obtained the album from the soldier's
relatives after his death in 1985, but the professor declined to
disclose the soldier's name.
</P>
<P>
According to the professor, the soldier was born in Osaka in
1911 and joined an artillery troop of the Japanese Tenth Army in
1937. After the war, he worked as an electrical engineer in
a Japanese company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Distance Runner Reaches NATO HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A Polish distance-running
specialist added on Monday another 1,400 kilometers to his career
mileage of already 120,000 kilometers by completing his run from
Warsaw to the NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Polish air force officer Wojciech Pismenko ran the last few
kilometers on Monday before reaching the headquarters of the
western military alliance and being welcomed by NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana and other NATO officials.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old runner held a Polish national flag during his
last kilometers of run in Brussels and described upon arrival his
run as a demonstration of the approach of the Polish people
toward the accession of his country to NATO.
</P>
<P>
Pismenko left the Polish capital on August 15 and averaged 58
kilometers, more than the distance of a classical marathon, for
the 24-day super run.
</P>
<P>
The Polish runner's career spanning 20 years includes 42
classical marathons of 42.195 kilometers, 14 super marathons of
100 kilometers each, 4 ultra-marathons of some 180 kilometers
covered in 24 hours non-stop, 2 48-hour-non-stop marathons and 1
super ultra-marathon between Athens and Sparta of 246 kilometers
run non-stop.
</P>
<P>
NATO has started accession talks with Poland along with
Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
The three eastern and central European countries are expected
to become full members of the military alliance early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
