<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Harbin Airport Gets New Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Yanjiagang Airport in Harbin,
capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, has changed
its name to Taiping (Peace and Tranquility) International Airport
with the approval of the Civil Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
First founded in 1979, the airport was originally used as an
emergency international airport and to receive chartered planes
from Japan, Southeast Asia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The only airport in this northeastern Chinese city, the newly
named Taiping underwent expansion in 1994 and is now certified as
an international advanced level facility.
</P>
<P>
It operates more than 30 domestic air routes, six regular
international routes and a dozen international charter-flight
routes.
</P>
<P>
Taiping Internatinal is now capable of handling large planes
such as Boeing 767s, and an annual passenger volume of 6.66
million. The airport handles 180 airplanes daily, with a
peak-hour passenger volume of up to 3,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
