<HEADLINE> Thai Main Opposition Party Delays Censure Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Leader of New Aspiration Party
(NAP), Thailand's largest political party and leading opposition
party, has promised to delay a censure debate against the Chuan
Leekpai government from November to January, the Nation newspaper
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, also NAP leader,
said the opposition wanted to give the current government, led by
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, more time to implement its economic
measures.
</P>
<P>
However, Chavalit warned Prime Minister Chuan against trying to
avoid the debate by dissolving the House first.
</P>
<P>
The opposition was likely to censure individual ministers, not
the entire cabinet, the newspaper quoted Chavalit as saying.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the government's attempts to solve the economic
crisis, Chavalit suggested the government build a canal across the
southern peninsula for a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said the so-called Kra Canal project would draw
foreign investment into Thailand and quickly revive the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, an adviser to Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi said the project would not be able to draw foreign
investment because the investors knew the project would take a
while to finish.
</P>
<P>
The current high interest rates in world markets would make the
project not worth the investment, the adviser said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
