<HEADLINE> Lebanon, World Bank Discuss Internet Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri Monday discussed with a World Bank delegation a program to
get Lebanon's secondary schools hooked to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Hariri told the delegation that he attaches great importance to
the plan, to be sponsored by the World Bank, in view of the
approach of the 21st century, which will feature advanced
technologies, the Lebanese Orient Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank launched a World Links for Development program
last year to get 1,500 secondary schools in 40 developing nations
connected with the Internet to partner schools in Australia,
Canada, European countries, Japan and the United States over a
four-year period.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at enabling the students to cooperate in
cultural, scientific and educational projects.
</P>
<P>
Hariri described the program as an opportunity to lead Lebanon
into a regional center for education on Internet.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent reduction in subscription fees to the
Internet is part of the Lebanese government's effort to help the
program succeed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Head of the World Bank delegation Shimse Diine said the program
will be carried out in Lebanon soon after a detailed plan is
worked out.
</P>
<P>
The program is currently operated in six African and five South
American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
