<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Needs $51 Billion to Avert Reserves Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea needs to increase
its foreign exchange reserves to 51.5 U.S. dollars billion to
avert a possible foreign exchange crisis caused by abrupt outflow
of hot money and a drastic shift in inter-Korean relations, the
Bank of Korea said Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea should gather enough dollars equaling a combination
of its current foreign exchange payments and 25 percent of its
short-term foreign debt to prepare for a possible outflow of hot
money, said the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the nation has to keep more dollars in preparation
for a possible outflow of foreign funds if the inter-Korean
relations deteriorate, the bank added.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, South Korea's current foreign
exchange payments, including import settlements, interest payment
on foreign debt, remittances, royalties, and expenses for overseas
transportation and travel, amounted to 64.2 billion dollars while
its short-term foreign debt stood at 38.3 billion dollars in June
this year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also predicted that some 9.8 billion dollars
will flow out of the nation's stock and bond markets if the
inter-Korean ties are further compromised.
</P>
<P>
Because of these factors, South Korea needs to increase its
foreign exchange reserves to 51.5 billion dollars from current
41.3 billion before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the world,
suffered a financial crisis caused by corporate bankruptcies and
bad loans of financial institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
The country signed an agreement with the International Monetary
Fund last December to borrow 58 billion dollars from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Expects Good Grain Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 7 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region is expected to yield a good grain harvest this
year despite severe natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
A local agricultural official said here recently that the
autonomous region will harvest 16 billion kilograms of grain this
year, which would set an all-time record.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia sowed grain on 6 million hectares of land this
year, 170,000 hectares more than last year, and nearly two-thirds
of this was sown in arid areas.
</P>
<P>
The local government built a number of new water conservancy
projects which added 146,000 hectares of irrigated land this year,
and farmers have begun using new techniques such as plastic
sheeting and coated seeds.
</P>
<P>
However, rainstorms during the flood season have destroyed 2
million hectares of crops, or one-third of the total cropland. The
floods have led to a loss of 2.5 billion kg of grains this year,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
People in the flooded areas have been urged to help themselves
and promote production by draining off water from farmland and
replanting fast-growing crops in the inundated areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
