<HEADLINE> Thailand Considers Setting Up Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Science, Technology and
Environment Ministry of Thailand is planning to establish an
independent authority to control the use of nuclear power in the
country, the Bangkok Post newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Pathom Yamkate, deputy secretary general of the Office
of Atomic Energy for Peace (OAEP), the newspaper said the
independent body is part of the preparation for the future nuclear
power once studies show it is feasible to build a nuclear power
plant in the country.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet two years ago set up a committee to study the
feasibility of constructing a nuclear power plant. The study is
expected to be finished within two years.
</P>
<P>
The Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand (EGAT),
meanwhile, has been conducting a public relations campaign in
southern provinces, which are considered appropriate sites for the
location of the planned nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
Those provinces are considered suitable since there is no
active fault, a small number of inhabitants and enough water
supply for the cooling system.
</P>
<P>
EGAT earlier included the construction of a 1000-megawatt plant
beginning in 2006 at a cost of 70 billion baht (1.75 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the plan has recently been shelved. EGAT officials
predicted that the project would face more delay because of the
reduced demand for electricity as a result of the economic crisis.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
