<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Take Measures to Protect Tigers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- It is necessary for the
Vietnamese government to take effective measures to combat illegal
hunting and trading of tigers and products made from their skins
and bones, said a senior government official.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Van Dang, deputy minister of Agriculture and Rural
Development, also urged to educate people about the need to
preserve all wild animals and to protect forests and bio-diversity
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to official reports on Monday, the number of tigers
in Vietnam is diminishing due to an over-exploitation of natural
forests, the economic growth in forest areas, a decline of prey
for tigers and the increasing tiger-hunting.
</P>
<P>
Only about 150-250 tigers are estimated to be living in remote
forests in Vietnam, compared with thousands in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry is drafting regulation on wild animal
protection and management, Dang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
