<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Club President on Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sight First China Action
project has helped 34,800 people suffering from cataracts to
regain their eyesight since it began one year ago.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pretty satisfied with the result," said Kajit Habanananda,
president of Lions Clubs International (LCI) which is conducting
the project with the Chinese government, during a recent interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
According to projected plan, between 1997 and the year 2001
some 1.75 million cataract operations will be performed, 250
medical teams will be dispatched to make rounds of villages and
remote or poor areas, 11,000 medical professionals will be
trained, 100 eye-disease departments will be set up in local
hospitals, and other technical assistance will be provided to
Chinese eye clinics.
</P>
<P>
Habanananda went on to say that to effect this plan, the LCI
has donated 15 million U.S. dollars to China, the largest sum the
country has ever received to help its disabled.
</P>
<P>
According to Habanananda, LCI's cooperation with China is the
"most pleasant and productive" among all the 50-odd countries
where Sight First Action has been conducted. "I'm sure that LCI's
cooperation with China will go ahead smoothly in the future," he
added.
</P>
<P>
China has a blind population of some nine million, the largest
in the world, and among these four million lost their eyesight to
cataracts.
</P>
<P>
Lions Clubs International, which was founded in 1917, began its
Sight First Action in 1990 with the aim of helping and assisting
the more than 40 million blind people around the world. So far,
more than one million suffering from cataracts have been lifted
out of darkness with the help of this project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
