<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli General Strike Ends, Schools Remain Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- About 300,000 Israeli public
workers ended a general strike Sunday after the main labor
federation reached an agreement over pay raises with the treasury
in the morning, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that representatives from both the Histadrut,
Israel's labor federation, and the Finance Ministry expressed
satisfactions over the agreement, the details of which were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut had threatened to intensify the strike Monday by
shutting down banks, the Ben-Gurion Airport and the stock
exchange, which have remained open since the general strike was
launched last Thursday, if all-night negotiations with the
treasury failed to reach a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides continued their talks in early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Government offices, railways, ports and other public services
had been closed down since the general strike began last week.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut was demanding an 8-percent wage rise for
public-sector workers, but the Finance Ministry refused to give
salary increases of more than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the teachers' strike continued Monday after another
last-minute talks with the treasury broke off Sunday night,
keeping about 2 million pupils out of their schools for the sixth
straight day.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' unions demand that they get payment for the time
they spend with their students on field trips and that the wages
for school principals be raised.
</P>
<P>
But the treasury objects to the requests, saying wage hikes for
the teachers would open the door to raises for other sectors of
the civil service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
