<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo on Strong Futures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices skyrocketed in
Tokyo Monday with the key Nikkei index posting its second biggest
single-day point advance this year, spurred by a sharp rise in
Nikkei futures.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange soared 747.15 points, or 5.32
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 14,790.06.
</P>
<P>
Investors rushed to buy shares across the board to fill
depleted arbitrage positions as Nikkei futures prices jumped more
than 900 points in Osaka.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, surged 38.18 points or 3.49 percent to
1,132.65.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 470
million shares from Friday's 447.54 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Shares opened lower but soon rebounded as the Nikkei futures
prices began to skyrocket. The price of the futures contract for
September delivery reached as high as 14,960 and ended at 14,930,
up 920 points from Friday.
</P>
<P>
While many traders suspected that U.S.-based hedge funds may
have made big purchases of futures contracts, others thought that
government-linked pension funds were also getting into the act.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,341 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
exceeded losers 986 to 185, with 125 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar sank 3 yen from
its Friday to the 131 yen level for the first time in four months
as market players, especially U.S. hedge funds, snapped up the
Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 131.98-132.00 yen at 5 p.m. local time
(0800 GMT), down from 133.15-18 yen at 9 a.m. and down from
135.40-42 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
