<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar Move to Promote Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Myanmar will kick
off a two-day official meeting here later this week to discuss how
to boost trade and investment between the two sides, a Thai
Commerce Ministry official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchapakdi will lead representatives from the government and
private sector to meet a Myanmar delegation led by Trade and
Commerce Minister Maj. Gen. Kyau Than, said the official, who did
not give his name.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also focus on problems concerning border
closure which was done by Myanmar's local authorities without
notifying Thai officials in advance, a ban on some imported goods
by the two countries, inconvenient transportation routes and high
charges of import fees by Myanmar customs officials.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the trade volume between the two
countries stood at 441.54 million U.S. dollars, with Thailand
mostly enjoying a trade surplus. Myanmar had a trade surplus only
in 1993 during which Thailand's export volume was 151 million
dollars against its import volume of 154.8 million dollars,
according to statistics provided by the Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
During the past six months, the trade volume was 204 million
dollars, a 31.8-percent drop from last year.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Thai Tak Chamber of Commerce has
urged the Myanmar authorities to temporarily open the Thai-Burmese
Friendship Bridge at the Myanmar side on September 9 to facilitate
the transport of goods and people between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Thailand initially agreed to open the bridge on
September 9. However, the local authorities in Myanmar recently
notified Thailand that they wanted to postpone the opening until
September 17, saying they were not yet ready. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
