<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Wants Thailand's Help for Joining ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Co-Prime Minister
Hun Sen has asked Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai to help
solve Cambodia's membership in the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEASN), a Foreign Ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Kobsak Chutikul said Hun Sen has
submitted a letter to Chuan via the Thai Embassy in Phnom Penh,
requesting him to ask the ASEAN foreign ministers who will meet in
New York at the end of this month to allow Cambodia to become an
ASEAN member, according to Monday's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak said Cambodia wants to take part in the ASEAN foreign
ministers meeting as an observer as a first step towards full
membership.
</P>
<P>
In the letter dated August 31, Hun Sen stated that Cambodia has
taken appropriate measures to respond positively to the ASEAN's
move to become politically and economically stronger to face the
challenges of the 21st century and the trend of regionalization
and globalization.
</P>
<P>
"Cambodia has always kept a strong commitment for ASEAN
membership to achieve ASEAN's founder vision of all ASEAN nations
in one ASEAN family," the paper quoted the letter as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is in this spirit that I have the honor to request your
excellency to give a favorable consideration to the question of
Cambodia's ASEAN membership at the next meeting of ASEAN foreign
ministers," Hun Sen said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen is set to become Cambodia's next prime minister
following the victory of his ruling People's Party in the July 26
elections. The ASEAN has announced its acceptance of the election
results.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups nine countries: Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
