<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Jews Settle in Palestinian Territories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of the Jewish
settlers in the Palestinian territories rose by 12.4 percent in
the 18 months ending June 30, the Israeli Interior Ministry said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The overall number of settlers rose by 8.8 percent between
during 1997, and by another 3.3 percent between the end of 1997
and June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Among the total 169,339 settlers, 163,173 are living in the
West Bank and 6,166 in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry has yet to gather and process the data
regarding July and August, which are traditionally marked by a
higher than average increase in the number of new settlers, as
families take advantage of summer vacation to move before the
beginning of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that half of the increase is due to natural
growth and the remaining because of new residents moving to the
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The figures further revealed that 86,202 settlers, slightly
more than half of the overall Jewish population in the
territories, live in only nine of the 144 settlements, including
Ma'aleh Adumim, Ariel, Givat Ze'ev, Efrat, Kiryat Sefer and
Betar.
</P>
<P>
The biggest increase in population in the past one year and a
half was registed in the ultra-Orthodox settlements of Kiryat
Sefer (55 percent) and Betar (35 percent).
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed that 80,418 of the settlers live in
what is known as the "depths of the territories," areas not
adjacent to densely populated areas within the Green Line, the
demarcation between Israel and the West Bank after 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
The remaining settlers live in greater Jerusalem or in
settlements along the Green Line in the Sharon area.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side said that a total of 190 Jewish
settlements exist in the territories, of which 173 are located in
the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen's Residence in Phnom Penh Blasted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 7 (Xinhua) -- An explosion occurred on
Monday morning in Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen's Phnom
Penh residence, which caused panic in the country's capital.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that someone threw three hand-grenades into the
house, and two of them exploded.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, who was in Siem Reap when the blast took place at 9:50
a.m. local time, flew back to Phnom Penh by a helicopter at noon.
</P>
<P>
Before departure from Siem Reap, he told reporters that it is
time to take actions against the organizers and leaders of the
demonstrations, which had lasted nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
"They wanted to murder me through terrorism and they even asked
the United States to launch a missile attack on my residence in
Takhmau," said Hun Sen, who had ordered to ban the demonstration
organizers and leaders from leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
Hok Lundy, national police director-general, said that the
attack was directed against Hun Sen, with an aim to end his
political life. "We are waiting for orders to take powerful
actions, but we will act in accordance with the law," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was the third explosion incident in Phnom Penh after the
National Assembly (parliament) elections were held on July 26.
</P>
<P>
The two major opposition political parties of the Funcipec led
by Prince Norodom Ranariddh and the Sam Rainsy Party of Sam Rainsy
have been holding demonstrations and sits-in after the elections.
</P>
<P>
They rejected the election result, claiming that there were
many frauds and demanding Hun Sen's resignation. They also said
that they would not join the new government led by Hun Sen as
prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
