<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- More than 20 Lebanese, including a woman, have been
arrested on suspicion of spying for Israel and involvement in the
recent killing by Israel of a guerrilla leader, the Daily Star
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The arrests followed a security sweep carried out in the past
few days by the Lebanese army in Beirut's southern suburbs, the
paper said. It was reported that the network was uncovered on a
tip from a man suspected of working for Israel and helping Israeli
troops in the assassination of Hussam Amin, Lebanon's anti-Israeli
Amal Movement southern commander, near the southern city of Tyre
last month. (Lebanon-Israel-Spying)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen accused
his political opponents of launching grenade attack on his
residence and threatened arrests.
</P>
<P>
"This is their (the opposition's) real revolution, like a real
coup d'etat," Hun Sen said shortly before leaving Siem Reap for
the capital. "It's time to arrest the organizers of the
demonstrations," Hun Sen said. Two grenades, hurled by four men
from a passing motorcycle, exploded in the compound of Hun Sen's
Phnom Penh residence Monday. (Cambodia-Hun Sen-Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- The flight data recorder of the doomed Swissair
Flight 111 that crashed off Canadian coast last week was recovered
Sunday, reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It was the flight data recorder," confirmed Vic Gerden, head
investigator for Canada's Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
The device was found about eight kilometers off the Canadian
coast, and it would be sent to Ottawa for analysis by a multi-
national team of investigators, the reports said.
(Canada-Swissair-Data Recorder)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MADRID -- The troops of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) "are ready to begin intervention" in the Yugoslav province
of Kosovo, the alliance's secretary-general Javier Solana said in
Madrid Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Solana warned that Yugoslavia must immediately stop its
military operations in Kosovo. Otherwise, NATO would intervene, he
said. However, Solana believed that a diplomatic solution is still
possible. He said that a peace proposal on stabilizing the
situation in Kosovo has been drafted and new contents are expected
to be added in the near future. (Spain-NATO-Kosovo) 
