<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Internet Surfers Emerge in China's Poorest Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Xin Xiaodong, 34, has been
spending some of his spare time on the Internet daily just like
other surfers around the world, and is now among the first group
of 22 Internet surfers in one of China's poorest areas.
</P>
<P>
Xin became an Internet user at the end of last year. The number
of 'Net surfers in Xihaigu Prefecture in northwest China's Ningxia
Autonomous Region now accounts for 3 percent of all Internet users
in Ningxia, China's smallest autonomous region (province).
</P>
<P>
China registered about 1.1 million net surfers by the end of
June this year.
</P>
<P>
Xihaigu is an outlying mountainous area with poor roads and
communications facilities, and 500,000 of its needy inhabitants
still live below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
But as part of the rapid economic growth now taking place in
Xihaigu, state-of-the-art telephone exchanges and optic fibre
cables have been installed in the region.
</P>
<P>
A local government official said that only six years ago most
of the local residents in Xihaigu knew little about computers, but
now many households have them.
</P>
<P>
Xin Xiaodong, mathematics teacher at Guyuan Teachers College,
spent 7,600 yuan (910 U.S. dollars) to buy a Compaq computer. This
represents nearly two years' salary.
</P>
<P>
Xin said, "It is worth it to buy the computer and become a
'Net surfer, as I gain more knowledge and my vision is widened,"
adding that his students are more interested in his lessons since he
has been absorbing so much new information over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The websites Xin usually visit are those of Chinese and foreign
university libraries. In the past, he had to go to Yinchuan,
capital of the autonomous region 400 km away from his home, to
find such information.
</P>
<P>
He said, "All I need now is a few stroke on the keyboard of my
computer when I want the latest information in a certain field."
</P>
<P>
The Internet also helps boost local economic growth. The
Haiyuan County government has already begun to issue information
on agricultural cooperation via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Hongxiang Company, a privately-run venture, signed an agreement
with a Shanghai venture to sell 4,000 tons of potatos through the
Internet this past June. Ningxia is famous for its rich-starch
large potatos and Chinese wolfberry fruit.
</P>
<P>
In Guyuan County, the center of Xihaigu Prefecture, three
computer shops have opened along the two-km-long main street, and
advertisements for computer training are popular in newspapers and
in shop-window displays.
</P>
<P>
The Guyuan Daily, the prefecture's only newspaper, will go
on-line this October and is expected to be the first to do so
among the region's media.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
