<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Food Exports To Asia Rose Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The lower Australian dollar
has helped buoy Australian food exports to Asia despite lower
demand from the Asia crisis hitting some order books, the
government-funded Supermarket to Asia group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jim Kennedy, executive director of the group, said total food
exports for the financial year of 1997-1998 ending on June 30,
1998, climbed to 18 billion Australian dollars (10.8 billion U.S.
dollars) from 17.2 billion Australian dollars the previous year.
</P>
<P>
But although exports to Asian nations rose slightly to 10.4
billion Australian dollars (5.9 billion U.S. dollars) from 10.2
billion Australian dollars, demand varied dramatically.
</P>
<P>
"Although we are seeing a very mixed response for food sales in
Asia, our figures clearly endorse the need to maintain a focus on
Asia for sales of Australian food products," Kennedy said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
He said exports of dairy, meat and horticultural products to
Indonesia suffered sharp falls, but demand for the same foods held
up well in nearby Malaysia and even rose in some cases in Japan
and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Overall sales to Indonesia, China, Taiwan, the Philippines and
Singapore fell and Indonesia's volatile outlook meant there was
little prospect of the former lucrative market recovering in the
short-term.
</P>
<P>
But Japan remained Australia's biggest customer for a wide
range of products with Australian exports to that destination
rising 8.8 percent over the financial year of 1997-1998 to about 5
billion Australian dollars (2.95 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a further bright spot, Australia's competitiveness had
gained a 25 percent advantage over U.S. products due to the weaker
Australian currency against the U.S. dollar, providing a window of
opportunity for Australia to substantially increase its share of
that key market.
</P>
<P>
As an advisory body to the Australian government on food export
to Asia, Supermarket to Asia was formed in late 1996 to provide
strategic export direction for the food industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 07:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Lebanese Arrested for Spying for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 Lebanese,
including a woman, have been arrested on suspicion of spying for
Israel and involvement in the recent killing by Israel of a
guerrilla leader, the Daily Star newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The arrests followed a security sweep carried out in the past
few days by the Lebanese army in Beirut's southern suburbs, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the network was uncovered on a tip from a
man suspected of working for Israel and helping Israeli troops in
the assassination of Hussam Amin, Lebanon's anti-Israeli Amal
Movement southern commander, near the southern city of Tyre last
month.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted security source as saying that the suspects
were said to be providing a Cyprus-based branch of the Israeli
intelligence service, Mossad, with information. But it did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
These latest arrests are considered separate from a spy ring
that the government said it uncovered last month.
</P>
<P>
In that case, 77 Lebanese were charged with passing information
to Israel on Lebanese and Syrian troop movement and activities of
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been engaged in a war of attrition in occupied south
Lebanon with resistance fighters since 1985, when it carved out a
1,200-square-kilometer, self-styled security zone there after two
invasions of Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
