<HEADLINE> New Zealand Government To Be Put for Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley is determined to test her Government's mandate
Tuesday as the New Zealand economy looks certain to slip into
deficit.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Monday, Mrs. Shipley announced that
she will seek leave in Parliament Tuesday to test the confidence
of the House in her National-led minority Government.
</P>
<P>
"The new Cabinet is in place and the new teams of ministers are
focused on the tasks in hand. It is now time to test our support
with a confidence debate and vote tomorrow afternoon," she said in
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The new Government was established on August 30 after the
collapse of the Coalition Government formed by the National Party
and NZ First. In composing the new Cabinet, Mrs. Shipley set up
six teams among the ministers. they are the Economic Team, the
Enterprise and Innovation Team, the Social Policy Team, the
Justice and Security Team, the New Zealand 2000 Team and the APEC
Team.
</P>
<P>
"The new Government will ensure that it delivers results for
New Zealanders by having ministers work effectively together in
six teams in order to work with New Zealanders, listen to them
carefully and deliver specific strategic results for them," she
said while announcing the namelist of the six teams.
</P>
<P>
In today's statement, Mrs. Shipley said that she expects the
new Government will win the confidence of the House.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the New Zealand Government is
likely to record a deficit after five years of surpluses.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand economic situation is "serious, but manageable,"
Mrs. Shipley said on television Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
