<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Notebook for Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- It took a total of 10 sets
and better than 6 hours, but half of the American contingent in
the men's draw at the U.S. Open was wiped out today.
</P>
<P>
Tenth seed Carlos Moya of Spain rallied to oust unseeded
Jan-Michael Gambill of the United States in a five-set duel that
lasted two minutes less than three hours. Moments later, Oliver
Gross of Germany took out American wild-card entry Geoff Grant,
also in five sets that took three hours, 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The losses by Gambill and Grant left top seed Pete Sampras and
eighth seed Andre Agassi as the only remaining American men.
Sampras and Agassi on course to face each other in the
quarterfinals if they survive their fourth round matches on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Greg Rusedski was the early favorite, going the
distance in his first two matches, but he fell in five sets
Saturday to drop out of the running. Moya lost the first two sets
to American Michael Chang in his second round showdown before
rallying to win in five in a match that ended about 1:30 a.m.
Friday morning. Today, he again fell behind 2-1 before surging
again to win.
</P>
<P>
Richard Krajicek needs surgery to repair damage in his left
knee. The only question for the Dutch star is when he opts to
have it.
</P>
<P>
Krajicek, seeded fifth at the Open, retired in the second set
of today's third round match against Thomas Johansson of
Sweden.Krajicek won the first set in a tiebreak and was down 4-5
in the second when he made the decision to stop.
</P>
<P>
"It is really been bothering me since the end of last
year,"said Krajicek. "I've been trying to play this year as long
as possible because I know I need an operation or I will tear my
meniscus. I was trying to postpone it as long as possible."
</P>
<P>
Tonight, several hundred chanting Chileans decked out in their
national colors and carrying flags and banners descended on the
National Tennis Center to cheer on second seed Marcelo Rios.
</P>
<P>
Rios is gunning for his first Grand Slam title and is hoping
to again displace American Pete Sampras as the top-ranked player
in the world.
</P>
<P>
During the first week of the tournament, eight men have been
fined for code of conduct infractions, with a high of 1,500
dollars
levied against Andrei Pavel of Romania for unsportsmanlike
conduct.
</P>
<P>
Only two fines have been levied against women, both against
Patricia Tarabini of Argentina. Tarabini has been fined 1,000
dollars for an audible obscenity and an additional 1,500 dollars
for a visible obscenity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
