<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Czech Republic's balance of payments improved visibly
in the first half of the year, a national bank spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During this period, spokesman Pavel Palivec said, the country's
balance of payments deficit dropped to 15.4 billion koruny (551
million U.S. dollars), just one-fourth of the level of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Palivec attributed the improvement to the favorable trend of
foreign trade. Foreign trade deficit was only 35.7 billion koruny
(1.19 billion dollars) in the first six months as against 74.7
billion koruny (2.49 billion dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
At present, balance of payments deficit accounted for only 1.8
percent of the country's gross domestic product, much lower than
in Poland, Hungary and other Central and East European countries.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) hailed the
Indonesian government's efforts in improving its banking system,
IMF director for Asia Pacific Hubert Neiss was quoted by local
newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This was a significant step that has been taken by the
government in its effort to rehabilitate the banking system. I was
glad to hear it," Neiss said upon arrival at Soekarno-Hatta
International airport here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In its latest move to restructure the banking sector, the
Indonesian government froze the operations of Bank Umum Nasional,
Bank Dagang Negara Indonesia and Bank Modern and took over the
ownership of Bank Central Asia, Bank Danamon, Bank PDFCI and Bank
Tiara.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether IMF would suggest further bank closures, Neiss
said he had not yet been informed about the next steps the
Indonesian government would take.
</P>
<P>
"But the government has to continue to improve the banking
sector because this is a prerequisite for recovery," he added.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO -- Maputo managed a better international trade fair this
year over that of last year, with 10,000 more visitors and two
more foreign countries participating in the fair, an organization
officer said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Amerrico Magaia, director-general of the Maputo International
Fair, an annual trade fair in the country, said about 170
companies, including firms from 11 foreign countries came to the
fair.
</P>
<P>
Last year nine foreign countries sent their companies to the
fair.
</P>
<P>
The trade fair attracted enterprises involved in industry,
tourism, agriculture, food-processing, computer and insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
