<HEADLINE> Czech Republic's Balance of Payments Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Czech Republic's balance of
payments improved visibly in the first half of the year, a
national bank spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During this period, spokesman Pavel Palivec said, the country's
balance of payments deficit dropped to 15.4 billion koruny (551
million U.S. dollars), just one-fourth of the level of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Palivec attributed the improvement to the favorable trend of
foreign trade. Foreign trade deficit was only 35.7 billion koruny
(1.19 billion dollars) in the first six months as against 74.7
billion koruny (2.49 billion dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the profit of tourism industry grew to 28.5
billion koruny (950 million dollars) from the 21.7 billion koruny
(720 million dollars) a year before.
</P>
<P>
At present, balance of payments deficit accounted for only 1.8
percent of the country's gross domestic product, much lower than
in Poland, Hungary and other Central and East European countries.
