<HEADLINE> Shanghai in A Bit to Lure More Overseas Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
city, plans to attract more overseas tourists through a series of
promotions to curb the downward trend of local tourism affected by
the current Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The programs include an international tourism fair, a tourism
festival, a world postal conference, a regional annual conference
on radio and television, and several sports games, according to
the Shanghai Municipal Tourism Commission.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that in the first half of the year the
number of overseas tourist arrivals to Shanghai was 729,200, down
seven percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, the tourist commission has sent 100
promotion teams to many foreign countries and regions including
Australia, New Zealand, England, France, Italy and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The authorities also have issued about 900,000 tourist guide
brochures and video tapes displaying Shanghai's scenic spots to
overseas agents.
</P>
<P>
Local tourist agents have also worked out many new types of
tours like "being a Shanghainese for one day," "honeymoon in
Shanghai" and "crossing the millennium."  
</P>
