<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis May Last 5 Years: Former NZ Envoy to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis
may last five years and has proved to be more serious than some
experts expected late last year, former New Zealand Ambassador to
China Bryce Harland told a recent meeting of the New Zealand
Institute of International Affairs in Wellington.
</P>
<P>
A prevailing view in December was that the problems in Asia
were part of the trade cycle and would be over in two years or so.
But the financial crisis grew to an economic one, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The general view now is that it will last longer -- more like
five years than two -- and have more serious consequences," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Harland noted that the Asian crisis highlighted the point that
New Zealand could not afford to "have too many eggs in one
basket."
</P>
<P>
"Diversification of markets, and of products, must remain our
strategy: we must be ready to exploit opportunities wherever they
occur," he said.
</P>
<P>
The opening of markets was essential for the return of
prosperity in Asia and for the continued stability and security of
the Asia-Pacific region, Harland noted.
</P>
<P>
The openness of the American market had been a fundamental
condition for export-led growth in Asia and it had so far helped
limit the tensions that have arisen over trade questions between
the United States and Asian countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Conversely the greatest danger at present is that the Asian
crisis may spark off a new round of protectionism in America,"
Harland said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that trade liberalization was therefore at the heart
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum's work for
both political and economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
The United States and other countries such as New Zealand had
been working hard to keep up the momentum of trade liberalization,
he said, adding New Zealand had succeeded in getting forestry and
fish products included in the package of proposals for early
liberalization due to be considered at the next APEC leaders
meeting in Kuala Lumpur later this year.
</P>
<P>
Harland said it would not be surprising if there was increased
resistance from some of the countries hardest hit by the crisis,
such as Thailand, South Korea, Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
By the time when the APEC leaders meeting was held in Auckland
in September 1999, there might well have been some slowing in the
process of liberalization, in individual economies, if not the
membership at large, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
