<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divers Found Swissair Flight Data Recorder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The flight data recorder of the
doomed Swissair Flight 111 that crashed off Canadian coast last
week was recovered Sunday, reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It was the flight data recorder," confirmed Vic Gerden, lead
investigator for Canada's Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
The device was found about eight kilometers off the Canadian
coast, and it would be sent to Ottawa for analysis by a
multinational team of investigators, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The so-called black box, if in good condition, will provide up
to 100 type of data that would help explain why the Swissair MD-11
jet crashed into the Atlantic, which killed all 229 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, divers will continue searching for the second black
box, the cockpit voice recorder that contain the last
conversations between the pilot and co-pilot as well as other
noises in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss plane, en route from New York to Geneva, crashed
about 60 kilometers southwest of Halifax, late Wednesday, about 16
minutes after the pilots reported smoke in the cockpit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
