<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Grows Steadily in North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Despite unfavorable
conditions as a result of Asian economic crisis, north China's
Hebei province reported steady development in foreign trade in the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The province completed 1.96 billion U.S. dollars of imports and
exports in the first six months, up 22 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed these achievements to the province's
restructuring of the foreign trade pattern.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded enterprises have become new growth points of
foreign trade in Hebei. Total imports and exports of
overseas-funded enterprises reached 930 million U.S. dollars in
the January-June period, up 32 percent over last year, and
accounted for 47 percent of the total imports and exports in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the customs office of Shijiazhuang, capital of
the province, show that trade based on processing is now the
pillar of foreign trade in Hebei. Export of processed products
amounted to 300 million U.S. dollars in the first half of this
year, up 7.2 percent over last year. High-tech enterprises
exported 300 million U.S. dollars' worth of goods, up 23 percent
over last year.
</P>
<P>
The province exported 450 million U.S. dollars' worth of
primary products, down 24 percent, 1.1 billion U.S. dollars' worth
of manufactured products, up 18.5 percent; and 190 million
U.S. dollars' worth of electro-mechanical products, up 16.5
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Documents on Russia, Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SALZBURG, Austria, September 6 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
foreign ministers Sunday urged Russian President Boris Yeltsin to
form a government and proceed with economic reforms as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
They made the appeal in a document adopted at the end of a
two-day conference in Salzburg, Austria. Russian political and
economic crisis dominated the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the constitutional procedures to form a new
government will soon be completed," said the document. "This will
help to reestablish confidence among the Russian people and the
international financial community."
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister and Chairman of the Council of
Foreign Ministers of the meeting Wolfgang Schuessel said after the
meeting that the EU will continue to help Russia out of its crisis
but will not offer fresh financial aid until the situation clears
up there.
</P>
<P>
"It is our firm conviction that political stability goes hand
in hand with economic stability and constitutes a prerequisite for
economic growth in Russia," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said the EU will send a "Troika" mission to
Moscow to help solve the problems. The mission will comprise
delegates from Austria, Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Russian crisis, which was triggered by rouble's mid-August
nosedive, became a central topic of the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
In another document adopted at meeting, the foreign ministers
also agreed to appoint an EU special envoy to help secure a
political settlement to the strife-torn Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
As part of the EU sanctions against Yugoslavia, planes from the
Yugoslav Airlines will be banned from landing in EU countries
starting next week, EU commission member in charge of external
affairs Van den Broek said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) not to take
violent actions in its bid to pursue independence, which he said
was against the EU's line.
</P>
<P>
Except for British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook who was on
holiday in France, all other 14 EU foreign ministers participated
in the meeting. 
</P>
