<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China's Yunnan to Expand Coffee Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province will add 3,133 hectares annually to its existing
coffee-growing area within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, by year 2000 the coffee-growing
area in the province will total 1,666 hectares producing 15,000
tons of dried coffee beans annually.
</P>
<P>
About 420 million yuan of investment will be needed to realize
this plan, and local governments at various levels in the province
will also investment in water control facilities in coffee-growing
regions.
</P>
<P>
Many areas of Yunnan are tropical and subtropical, providing
suitable natural conditions for growing small coffee beans.
</P>
<P>
The province, first in China in the production and processing
of coffee beans, now sows 7,333 hectares of coffee and produces
3,500 tons of dried coffee beans annually.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the International Coffee Organization say that
small coffee beans grown in Yunnan are nearly the equal of the
well-known Columbia coffee beans in quality.
</P>
<P>
The coffee giants Maxwell and Nestle companies have both signed
contracts with Yunnan to provide them with 10,000 tons of beans by
the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
China now consumes about 10,000 tons of coffee beans a year, 70
percent of which are imported. This figure is expected to rise to
20,000 tons by year 2000.
</P>
<P>
While working out a plan for developing its coffee industry,
the Yunnan Provincial Government has decided to set up a center
for coffee research and related processing
technology. Preparations have been made to construct a coffee
bean-trading market, said local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Linguist Calls for Intensified Courses on Old Chinese language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Guo Xiliang, a well-known
linguist, has called for further education and research on ancient
Chinese, the world's sole existing ancient language.
</P>
<P>
Guo, a professor at Beijing University, said that ancient
Chinese refers to the language used before the Opium War
(1840-1842). It was developed from ancient written language based
on oral terms in the Qin Dynasty (221-207 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The language is still used, and universities re-opened courses
on ancient Chinese in the early 1980s. Students for art degrees
are required to take one-year credit course (four hours per week)
on the subject. But Guo said that is not sufficient.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that youngsters should learn more about ancient
Chinese in middle school before they enter college, he said, and
being able to read ancient Chinese is very helpful to their work
after graduation.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, research on ancient Chinese is important to
develop traditional Chinese culture and linguistic theory, he said.
</P>
<P>
Research and education on ancient Chinese is always on the top
of the work list for educational departments not only on Chinese
mainland but also in Hong Kong and Taiwan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Guo, 70, has printed more than one million copies of teaching
material on ancient Chinese for use by students, teachers and
linguistic researchers.
</P>
<P>
The field has attracted the interest and concern of scholars
and experts worldwide. China has hosted dozens of international
seminars on the grammar of ancient Chinese and the relationship
between the Chinese and Tibetan languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refuse from Coal Mines Fuels Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Refuse, slurry and other
byproducts of coal-mining used to be occupy thousands of hectares
of farmland, but nowadays Chinese engineers have developed a
technology to turn this waste into electricity.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's No.1 coal producer. In 1997, China turned
out 1.3 billion tons of raw coal which contained more than 100
million tons of refuse.
</P>
<P>
So far, 79 power plants with refuse and slurry as fuel have
been built in China since 1982, when the first such plant was put
into operation in the Pingxiang Coal Mine in east China's Jiangxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
With a combined capacity of 990,000 kilowatts, these power
plants are capable of generating more than 4 billion
kilowatts/hour of electricity annually, by consuming 15 million
tons of refuse and slurry.
</P>
<P>
Some refuse-fueled power stations have even been using dregs to
make cement and bricks.
</P>
<P>
China's success has drawn worldwide attention. In 1983, Chinese
scientists made public their new technology in an academic paper
delivered to a United Nations-sponsored international
symposium. Since then, more than 20 foreign experts have visited
the country to learn about the latest developments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Save More, Invest Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents of this economic
and financial center of China have shown increasing interest in
saving money in their personal accounts and declining interest in
buying stocks, an official sample survey indicates.
</P>
<P>
The value of savings per household increased by 1,047 yuan in
the first seven months of this year, about 4.5 times the
corresponding figure of last year, according to the findings of
the survey, which was conducted by the municipal statistics bureau
and based on 500 urban families.
</P>
<P>
However, the investment in stocks and other securities averaged
merely 130 yuan per family in the first six months, a plunge of 55
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai families also purchased an average of 340 yuan worth
of savings-type insurance in the first half of this year, a surge
of 26 percent on a yearly basis, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that Shanghai residents' change of habits in
managing money indicate that people are getting increasingly
aware of financial risks at a time when the Asian financial crisis
still lingers.
</P>
<P>
Residents with unstable incomes have saved more in anticipation
of future spending needs, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
The continued bearish stock market since this year has also
increased investment risks and resulted in many investors losing
money, adversely affecting people's enthusiasm for buying stocks,
they say.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates have put the average total savings value of
Shanghai residents at 20,000 yuan, in addition to an average of
2,000 yuan worth of stocks and securities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
