<HEADLINE> NATO Ready to Intervene in Kosovo: Solana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The troops of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) "are ready to begin
intervention" in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, the alliance's
secretary-general Javier Solana said in Madrid Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Solana warned that Yugoslavia must immediately stop its
military operations in Kosovo. Otherwise, NATO would intervene,
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Solana believed that a diplomatic solution is still
possible. He said that a peace proposal on stabilizing the
situation in Kosovo has been drafted and new contents are expected
to be added in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Solana emphasized that the Kosovo issue must be solved by this
winter. Otherwise, he said, failing to do so will bring even more
serious consequences to the 170,000 displaced people in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a Yugoslav province, where ethnic Albanians make up
90 percent of the total population. More than 300 people have
been killed since the outbreak of conflict between
separatist-minded ethnic albanians and Yugoslav police.
</P>
<P>
As Yugoslavia is strongly opposed to any foreign interference
in the conflict, the U.S.-led NATO has repeatedly threatened the
use of military force for a settelement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
