<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Migrate for More Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- "East, west, home is
best." This old saying was deep-rooted among Chinese farmers for
generations.
</P>
<P>
But these days, migration has become such a trend that more and
more farmers are leaving their home villages to find their fortune
in other localities.
</P>
<P>
Lu Guoxin, a young farmer in North China's Hebei Province,
recently joined the growing army of migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, going to town would be a long trip for Lu's
father, but Lu and his fellow villagers decided to go to the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, thousands of miles away from his
home, to grow cotton.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that the climate in Xinjiang is the best for cotton
growing and the prices of land and labor there are cheaper. "We
will go to any place where we can make more money," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Provincial Agriculture Department of Hebei
Province said thousands of Hebei farmers are now engaging in
aquaculture or vegetable growing in other provinces, and about
800,000 farmers from other provinces are working as migrant
laborers in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
Instead of blindly rushing into the cities, migrant farmers now
think more about how to give full play to their own advantages.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Dakuang, a farmer from East China's Anhui Province, gave
up his job at a company and went to farm in the suburb of Shanghai
recently.
</P>
<P>
He contracted for 26 mu (about 1.3 hectares) of land and
employed five men as helpers. His annual income has now reached
50,000 yuan, ten times more than he earned at the company.
</P>
<P>
He said, "As a skilled farmer, I can gain more benefits in the
countryside of the developed areas."
</P>
<P>
An official of the Hebei Provincial Government said migrant
work facilitates the flow of labor sources in the countryside and
helps more farmers become rich through their own sweat and toil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Graf Upset by Schnyder in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Patty Schnyder, the secret
weapon on the women's tour this year, registered the biggest
upset of the U.S. Open tennis championships tonight as she
stunned five-time champion Steffi Graf of Germany 6-3, 6-4 and
advanced to the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Ranked 10th in the world, Schnyder took advantage of Graf's
erratic play to win the first three games of the match and held
on to take the first set. She broke Graf in the ninth game of the
second set to go up 5-4 and served it out to complete the upset
in just 59 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Schnyder, a 19-year-old left-hander from Switzerland who plays
in the shadow of countrywoman Martina Hingis, has quietly surged
to the top of the women's tour in titles this year with five. She
will play Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic, world number two
player in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
"I was nervous at the start but when I got early break I
settled down," Schnyder said. "I also was a little nervous at the
end but I relied on my serve to her backhand and it worked."
</P>
<P>
Graf entered the tournament seeded eighth after winning the
Pilot Pen international last week.
</P>
<P>
"I'm just disappointed with the way the match went," Graf
said. "I had been playing better but tonight was a setback. I can
do better than that. I tried to get my feet going in the second
set but I was hitting short and I just couldn't get anything
going."
</P>
<P>
Schnyder won the match on her second match point when Graf
sent a backhand service return long. Just moments before,
Schnyder blew a match point when she was wide with a forehand
down the line with Graf totally out of position.
</P>
<P>
"Your could get intimidated playing her but you have to get
that out of your mind and try to treat her like another opponent,
"Schnyder said.
</P>
<P>
Graf was wild from the outset, making an unforced errors in
losing the first three games, and never seemed to gain control of
her shots.
</P>
<P>
Graf committed 33 unforced errors with only 14 winners, while
Schnyder had 13 winners and 24 unforced errors. Graf also was
unable to capitalize on her chances, winning only one of five
break point opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Graf, who won the 1995 and 1996 Opens but missed last year's
event due to an injury, believes Schnyder has what it takes to
become a dominant player on the women's circuit.
</P>
<P>
"She's good. She has a lot of potential. I thin she can be a
top-five player within the next couple of years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island to Uses Alternative Fuel to Produce Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, provincial capital of
the island province of Hainan off the southern tip of the Chinese
mainland, plans to make use of rubbish to supplement the city's
power supply with a new technology jointly developed by Finland
and Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
Work is underway to assess the feasibility of the project.
</P>
<P>
The new technology transforms rubbish into renewable fuel and
biological gas, which can be utilized to produce electricity. The
magnetic metal separated during the process can be recycled, and
the final residue is biological humus soil. The new technology can
reduce the amount of rubbish amount by 85 to 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Haikou produces 800 tons of rubbish each day, and it buries
most of it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
