<HEADLINE> Listed Breweries Report Good Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Spirits manufacturers listed
on China's two stock exchanges -- Shanghai and Shenzhen -- have
enjoyed better performance than other listed companies.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute their performance to improved standards of
living which have bolstered development of the industry over
the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the output of spirits, including
beer, fruit and rice wines and alcohol has increased at an annual
rate of nearly 50 percent since China launched its reform and
opening drive in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 output for spirits stood at 27 million tons, and it is
expected to reach 29 million tons by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of April show that 13 companies,
including a rice wine producer, seven liquor distillers, four beer
breweries and a winery, had been listed at the exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Annual reports for all producers recorded profits, with average
per share profits standing at 0.54 yuan, almost doubled the average
for all listed companies.
</P>
<P>
The Wuliangye Company, one of the nation's top distillers,
ranked with a profit/earnings rate of 1.42 yuan per share.
</P>
<P>
Other similar companies enjoyed a 22.37 percent increase in
total profits over the previous years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that China's distilleries constantly have
improved products and enjoy stablized output, with the growth of
breweries showing some slowness and rice wine producers enjoying
vast potentials.
</P>
<P>
Local wineries exhibit excellent potential, but have to
undertake technical upgrades in time to face growing competitions
from foreign competitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
