<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Turkey Deny Building Military Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Turkey renewed their
denial Sunday that they are trying to build a military alliance to
contain other states in the Mideast region.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent, and visiting Turkish
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz made the denial at a joint press
conference after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
There has never been such an initiative or mechanism of a
Jordanian-Turkish military alliance in any kind and there is no
need to discuss such an issue, said Hassan.
</P>
<P>
What Jordan and Turkey have been doing is just out of "a
concern for the region's security," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been making efforts to promote dialog
among all parties concerned and finally help bring "safety and
security" for all the countries in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Turkey, together with Israel, which receive large
economic and military aid from the U.S. every year, have been long
considered as trying to build a military alliance to help the
U.S. control the region.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the allegation that the U.S. is behind the planned
military alliance, Hassan said that Jordan is "not to be
manipulated" by outside force.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz echoed Hassan's remarks, saying that Turkey and Jordan
share similar views on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Turkey does not want to enter any military alliance, instead,
it hopes to build a multilateral conflict-prevention system
through its contacts and cooperation with all the concerned
parties, including Jordan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz arrived here earlier Sunday on a two-day official visit
to discuss military and economic cooperation with Hassan and his
counterpart Fayez Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
After his visit to Jordan, Yilmaz will go on to the Palestinian
self-rule areas and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
