<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Supports U.S. Mideast Peace Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz said here Sunday that the peace proposal put forward
by the U.S. to call for a 13.1 percent Israeli troops withdrawal
from the West Bank has been the best solution for the peace
deadlock so far.
</P>
<P>
If the peace proposal is accepted by both Israel and the
Palestinians, it will be a "very good opportunity" for both sides
to reactivate the peace process and help bring stability to the
region, said Yilmaz at a joint press conference with Jordanian
Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz added that Turkey also welcomes other peace proposals
put forward by some European countries, including those of France
and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. put forward its proposal months ago in an effort to
revive the 18-month deadlock of the peace process. The
Palestinians accepted it, but Israel rejected it on security
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is not an actual participant in the activities of
reviving the Palestinian-Israeli peace process, but it keeps
strong military ties with the Jewish state and receives large
military and economic aid from the U.S. annually.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz arrived here earlier Sunday on a two-day official
visit to discuss military and economic cooperation with Hassan
and his counterpart Fayez Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
He is also scheduled to visit the Palestinian self-rule
areas and Israel later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
