<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Meetings With Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Sunday denied reports that he had held a series
of secret meetings with Palestinians and achieved progress over
the Israeli further redeployment in West Bank.
</P>
<P>
At the weekly cabinet meeting, Netanyahu declared as untrue
media reports that he and Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker
Ahmed Queria (Abu Ala) had met three times in the last few days,
Israel Radio quoted Israeli Science Minister Silvan Shalom as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The denial came after a number of ministers, led by National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, complained that they were
not informed of the reported meetings.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Abu Ala had held 10 rounds of talks with
Israeli officials in the last two weeks, including three with
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said that the talks had yielded a draft
agreement on some key issues, including the scope of the second
Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank, the security
cooperation, the operation of a Palestinian airport and a sea port
in Gaza, and the release of Palestinian prisoners held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said at the meeting that there was progress in the
negotiations several weeks ago over an Israeli proposal that it
withdraw from 10 percent of the West Bank and turn an extra 3
percent into a "nature reserve," in which Israel will retain full
security responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Since then, however, nothing new had been produced, the prime
minister said, adding that Israel was now demanding that the two
sides return to the previous framework.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the coming visit to the region by U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross, Netanyahu said Ross would help classify the 3
percent of the West Bank which Israel and the Palestinians have
disputes over its nature.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have demanded that the land be designated as
"Area B" which under signed agreements will eventually become
areas fully controlled by them.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu reiterated that an agreement on the second Israeli
withdrawal depended upon the fulfillment by the Palestinians of
their security commitments and "an entire package of reciprocity."
</P>
<P>
Ross is expected to arrive in Israel Wednesday to help bridge
the remaining gaps between Israel and the Palestinians. He will
hold separate talks with Netanyahu and Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
