<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani FM Mediates Between Iran, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign
Minister Sartaj Aziz arrived Sunday in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, for a
visit reportedly dealing with the on-going Iranian-Afghan crisis,
the Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
Aziz held a meeting shortly after his arrival with his Saudi
counterpart Prince Saud Al-Faisal on a number of regional and
international issues. He also conveyed a message to Saudi First
Deputy Prime Minister Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz from
the Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Representative of the Afghan Taliban regime in Riyadh Mawlawi
Shehab Eddine Dalawer disclosed in a statement to Kuna that Aziz's
visit concerned "understanding between Pakistan and Saudi Arabia
on the recent crisis between Afghanistan and Iran."
</P>
<P>
Tension has heightened between Tehran and the Afghan Taliban
regime since Iran accused the Taliban of kidnaping 11 Iranian
diplomats and one journalist when the Taliban forces seized the
city of Mazari Sharif in northern Afghanistan on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Since the Taliban is only recognized by Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and Pakistan, the Iranian government has
recently asked Saudi Arabia to play a go-between role to secure
the release of the kidnaped Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has also held Pakistan, a strong supporter of the
Taliban, responsible for the abduction of the Iranian diplomats
and asked Islamabad to use influence on the Taliban to set them
free.
</P>
<P>
Iran, which has stationed some 70,000 troops close to the
Afghan border, has notified the U.N. Security Council that it
would resort to force to secure the freedom of the diplomats in
accordance with the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating the denial that Taliban was holding any
Iranians, Dalawer said that his government welcomed any mediation
role by Saudi Arabia and Pakistan concerning the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has not officially said whether it will play any
mediation role. But Kuna quoted informed sources as saying that
the Saudi foreign minister assured his Iranian counterpart during
the Non-Aligned Movement summit in Durban, South Africa, that
Saudi Arabia was ready to help defuse the tension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
