<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opinions Differ on Censure Suggestion in Lewinsky Matter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Senator Joseph Lieberman,
the Democrat who last week voiced unhappiness with U.S. President
Bill Clinton's handling of the Lewinsky affair, said Sunday he
hoped Clinton would suffer no more than a congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
But Senate Republican Leader Trent Lott said that was unlikely
to happen.
</P>
<P>
Another Democrat, Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan said Congress
should carry out its constitutional duty and decide whether
Clinton should be held accountable for impeachable offenses, but
he said he did not know how he would vote on removing the
president from office.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman said on NBC's "Meet the Press" that he believed
Clinton could restore his credibility with the nation and
successfully finish out his term in office. Lieberman said he
hoped that some kind of "public rebuke," such as a congressional
vote of censure, "will be the maximum we will want to do to end
this sad chapter in our history."
</P>
<P>
But there were lawmakers who suggested that censure wouldn't
suffice.
</P>
<P>
Lott, who again questioned whether Clinton now had the moral
authority to lead the nation, said censure was "not likely"
because "I don't think the circumstances now call for something
that could be interpreted by anybody as nothing."
</P>
<P>
Asked on NBC about Clinton's moral authority, Lott said,"I've
to say obviously there is some doubt about that now, based on what
we already know. But I think we have to wait and see what comes
out in the (independent counsel Kenneth) Starr report."
</P>
<P>
Representative Jim Moran, a Democrat, said on "Fox News Sunday"
that Clinton would be "very fortunate" if all he got was a
congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
"I now don't think that that is really an option," Moran said.
"I think we're bound to go through with impeachment proceedings."
</P>
<P>
Moran said the president's credibility "is severely diminished"
by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Senator Phil Gramm, a Republican, said it was almost certain
the House of Representatives would consider articles of
impeachment. "I think we have passed the point where we might wish
this away," he said on CBS' "Face the Nation."
</P>
<P>
Senator Robert Torricelli, a Democrat, said on CBS' "Face the
Nation" that "at the moment" the nation was still distinguishing
between the president's personal problems and his economic and
social accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
Torricelli said a decision by Maryland Governor Parris
Glendening to cancel a fund-raiser with Clinton was "not
indicative of what is happening around the country" and that
candidates for the Senate continued to seek appearances by
Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
