<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Jordanians in Extreme Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordanians living in extreme
poverty climbed to 8 to 11 percent of Jordan's total population in
1997, a 6.5 to 9.5 increase compared with the figures in 1986,
according to a census published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In Jordan, with a population of 4.6 million, families earning
less than 106 U.S. dollars a month are classified as extreme poor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the census, conducted by the state-run Irbid
University, said that 21 to 22 percent of Jordanians, whose
families have a monthly income of below 170 dollars, lived in
absolute poverty in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Jordan Times has reported that almost a
third of the kingdom`s total population live under the general
poverty line, with the family income below 210 dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
The census report attributed the expanded poverty to a
snail-paced regional economy, which, in fact, hindered Jordan's
economic development, incurring more unemployment and decreasing
people's income by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's annual population growth rate is 3.6 percent, among
the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The official unemployment rate in 1998 is put at 15 percent
while at 26 percent by independent sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish-Israeli Military Cooperation Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz said here Sunday that the Turkish-Israeli military
cooperation "is not directed against any country in the region,"
but only for the sake of regional "safety and security."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel expect that such cooperation will help
achieve a "comprehensive peace" in the region and then bring
about a multilateral conflict-prevention system, said Yilmaz at a
joint press conference with Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan, the
Regent.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has signed two military cooperation agreements with
Israel since 1996. It allows Israeli jets to use its airspace for
training, while Israel upgrades Turkey's F-4 fighters under a
contract worth 630 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Israeli military cooperation incurred harsh
criticism from some Arab countries who insist that it harms
regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries also accused Jordan, Israel and Turkey of
trying to build a military alliance to control regional
situation. Both Jordan and Turkey rejected the accusation.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, Israel and Turkey are usually considered as military
partners that are shouldered with the common obligation of
helping the U.S. stabilize the region. All of them receive large
quantities of economic and military aid from the U.S. on annual
basis.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz arrived here earlier Sunday on a two-day official
visit to discuss military and economic cooperation with Hassan
and his counterpart Fayez Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to visit the Palestinian self-rule areas and
Israel later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
