<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Exports to New Markets Up by 255 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's exports to its
non-traditional markets, mostly in eastern Europe and Africa,
increased by 255 percent in the first half of this year over the
same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom's exports to Eritrea, Portugal, Uganda, Bosnia,
Ethiopia, Hungary, Tanzania and New Zealand reached a total of
27,548.5 million Jordanian dinars (38,910.31 million U.S. dollars)
in the first six months of this year, said the report released by
the state-owned Export Development and Commercial Centers
Corporation (JEDCCC).
</P>
<P>
The exports increased by such a large margin because many new
commodities like medicine, textiles, detergents and processed
foodstuff were added to the previous year's list which included
phosphate, potash and cement, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The increase could also be attributed to the efforts made by
the JEDCCC together with Jordan's private sector to tap the
potential of the relatively new markets in eastern Europe and
Africa, it added.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the kingdom's trade development strategy in the
future, the report said that Jordan will further develop the
non-traditional markets, while trying to reverse a sliding trend
of its exports to the traditional markets.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's traditional markets are mainly in the Middle East,
which include Saudi Arabia, Iraq, the United Arab Emirates, Syria,
Lebanon, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's exports to its traditional markets fell by some 6
percent to 381 million dinars (538 million dollars) during the
first five months in 1998 from the same period last year, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the decrease of Jordan's exports to its
traditional markets to Amman's perceived tilt over Iraq during
the 1990-91 Gulf crisis which angered Jordan's neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Killed, 8 Injured in Road Accident in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Seven people were killed
and eight others injured in a road accident in Midrand,
Johannesburg, Sunday evening, SABC TV reported.
</P>
<P>
The victims were soccer fans who had just watched a premier
league match in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Six died instantly and another died on the way to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Although the cause of the accident has not been officially
established, it is believed that the driver of the minibus lost
control of the vehicle and veered into a ditch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
