<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Cities Aim at Reach Economy of Scale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- China's coastal cities are
aiming at developing their port-based economies on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
As the largest port in China, Shanghai has long handled more
than 150 million tons of freight a year.
</P>
<P>
"Without the support of sea transportation, Shanghai could
never become an economic, financial and trading center on a world
scale in the coming century," said Han Zheng, deputy mayor of
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Other major ports are also developing international trade and
economic and technological cooperation. They have set up economic
developmental areas and high-technology zones near their ports.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, a major port in North China, is launching a large
project to form a new coastal area based on its port, a
development area and free trade zone, which includes some
industrial programs involving large amounts of foreign investment
from transnational companies such as Dupont.
</P>
<P>
The ports of Lianyungang and Rizhao each handle more than 20
million tons of freight a year. While expanding the size of their
ports, the two cities are accelerating the construction of the
infrastructure and some important industrial projects near the
harbor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
