<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate to Take Up Campaign Finance Overhaul Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott Sunday promised to allow the Senate to take up
legislation that would change campaign finance laws, predicting
that the measure would come up for a vote as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
The bill was abandoned earlier this year by the Senate after
supporters failed to bring the issue before the full body. During
a news conference last week, Lott omitted the topic as he outlined
his priorities for the final weeks of Congress.
</P>
<P>
In August, the House of Representatives voted 252-279 to
approve a similar campaign finance bill, giving hope to the Senate
measure's two primary sponsors, Senator John McCain, a Republican,
and Senator Russell Feingold, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
The legislation would ban much of the so-called "soft money" --
unregulated big donations that now flows indirectly into
campaigns. Lott said that after the Senate rejected the bill
earlier this year, McCain agreed not to resurrect the issue. Last
month's passage of the House bill, however, changed that.
</P>
<P>
"He (McCain) maintains that the House voted, circumstances have
changed and he would like another vote," Lott said on NBC's "Meet
the Press." "I think that under the circumstances we should do
that and, yes, there will be another vote, yes, probably next
week."
</P>
<P>
However, Lott cast doubt on whether there were enough votes for
the measure to pass. "I don't believe that the consensus is there
yet," he said.
</P>
<P>
During a news conference last week McCain and Feingold said
that they would force a Senate vote on their bill by attaching it
to whatever legislation lawmakers happen to be considering.
</P>
<P>
Senator Carl Levin, a Democrat and a senior member of the panel
that investigated campaign finance abuses, said that he had no
problem advocating a "dramatic, old-fashioned filibuster" if
Republicans tried to block a vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
