<HEADLINE> U.S. Northwest, Pilots Negotiators Meet Mediator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal mediator
Sunday med separately with negotiators for Northwest Airlines
Corp. and the striking pilot union in an effort to restart
contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The 6,200 pilots from the airline went on strike on August 29
after almost two years of negotiations failed to yield a new
contract.
</P>
<P>
The talks broke off over wage increases and job security. A key
difference between the two sides is that the union was asking for
the "industry leading" wages, but the company refused to accept
it, arguing that it was only the fourth major airline in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
The pilots, along with five other unions negotiating with
Northwest, made concessions to pull the airline back from the
brink of bankruptcy in 1993 and now want to share in the record
profits the airline has posted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The strike affects about 150,000 passengers daily, especially
in Minneapolis, Detroit and Memphis where Northwest controls 75
percent of flights.
</P>
<P>
The strike forced Northwest to cancel 1,700 daily flights
through the busy Labor Day holiday and in-bound flights from
Europe and Asia through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first strike at Northwest in 20 years, and the first
to shut down a major U.S. airline since 1993, when flight
attendants at American Airlines went on strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
