<HEADLINE> Palestinians Cast Doubt Over U.S. Envoy's Upcoming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians have pinned
little hope on U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross' upcoming
Mideast trip, Egypt's Middle East News Agency said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Farouk Qadoumi, chairman of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization Political Department Sunday cast doubt over Ross'
ability to broker a Palestinian-Israeli deal on the Israeli
reployment in the West Bank, saying "Ross is a failure."
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time that Ross has come to the Middle
East, but the peace process which has been stalled since March
last year, has made little progress.
</P>
<P>
The senior Palestinian official said Israel does not want peace
and keeps on raising tensions in the Mideast region, the senior
Palestinian official said.
</P>
<P>
Qadoumi made the remarks after a meeting with Arab League (AL)
Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Ross' new Mideast trip will begin next week with an aim to
narrow differences between the two sides on a U.S. initiative for
an Israeli withdrawal from 13 percent more of the West Bank in
exchange for Palestinian security guarantee.
</P>
<P>
If Ross secures a breakthrough, the leaders of the two sides
would meet to seal a long-delayed deal on redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Though signs of some progress emerged this week after Clinton
telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat, neither
side confirmed any substantial headway.
</P>
<P>
Referring to talks with Abdel-Meguid, Qadoumi said they
discussed means of mobilizing Arab efforts to break the deadlocked
peace process, the agenda of the upcoming session of the AL
Ministerial Council scheduled for September 16 in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Qadoumi said he also briefed the secretary on the outcome of
the Non-Alignment Movement summit held recently in Durban, South
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
