<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Lebanon to Set up Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Lebanon will sign an
agreement on the establishment of a free trade zone between them
this week, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be sealed when the Egyptian-Lebanese Higher
Ministerial Committee meet in Cairo on Wednesday under the
co-chairmanship of Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal al-Ganzouri and
his Lebanese counterpart Rafik al-Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili said Sunday
after being sanctioned during the Higher Committee meetings, the
agreement should be ratified by the parliaments of both states
before putting it into force, he said.
</P>
<P>
Duing the first Egyptian-Lebanese Higher Committee session in
Cairo in March 1996, two agreements on protecting and encouraging
investments and preventing dual taxation were signed. Lebanese
investments in Egypt have reached 115 projects worth 55 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese side wishes to market apples in Egyptian markets
within the framework of goods exempted from custom fees and Egypt
wants to have its potatoes treated similarly in Lebanon, he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's exports to Lebanon reached 109.7 million dollars last
year, while imports stood at 59.4 million dollars, according to
Gowaili.
</P>
<P>
Egypt exports to Lebanon potatos, rice, onions, polyester and
railway roads, while Lebanon exports to Egypt apples and
publications, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has forged free trade agreements with Morocco and Tunisia
and plans to conclude similar pacts with Jordan, Kuwait, Bahrain
and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
As a prelude to the Arab common market, an Arab free trade area
has been kicked off since the beginning of this year, paving the
way for complete liberalization by the end of 2007 by eliminating
non-tariff barriers and phasing off tariffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-06 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Labor Union Threatens to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Labor Union
reiterated on Sunday that if no progress is made in the talks with
the Finance Ministry, it will intensify the public sector strike.
</P>
<P>
Labor Union Chairman Amir Perez, who is scheduled to hold
negotiations with Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman on Sunday night,
told Israel Radio that the strike might spread to other sectors.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if the Finance Ministry does not make compromise,
the strike will spread to banks and electricity corporations.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Union launched the strike on Thursday in protest
against the low wage of the workers in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The strike kept 300,000 workers away from their jobs and
resulted in the closure of all government offices, post offices,
railways, ports and some hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry had agreed to a 1.4 percent wage
increase, while the Labor Union demands an 8 percent rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
