<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Cabinet Approves Measures on Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait decided on Sunday
to adopt DNA test as an unwavering basis to grant nationality to
illegal residents, known as Bedoun, or stateless.
</P>
<P>
This is in a four-point plan approved by Kuwait's council of
ministers to solve the outstanding Bedoun problem, said the Kuwait
News Agency (Kuna).
</P>
<P>
During its weekly session, the council also decided to
intensify the "checking and confirmation of the data, documents
and testimonials that verify applications for nationality by
resorting to all means possible."
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration of the human perspective, the
council decided to prolong the easing of facilities for those
seriously seeking to amend their legal status, Kuna said.
</P>
<P>
The Bedoun problem has been a tough issue facing the Kuwaiti
government for years. The council of ministers set the year 2000
as the deadline to issue citizenship to Bedouns.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the Kuwaiti government will punish any
violators of the nationality law after the deadline.
</P>
<P>
According to an official study submitted to the cabinet last
week, there are approximately 120,000 Bedouns residing in Kuwait
at present, or some 17 percent of Kuwaiti population. Many Bedouns
have dumped their passports in the hope of obtaining Kuwaiti
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The study divided Bedouns into several groups: Bedouns of
Kuwaiti fathers, Bedouns of Kuwaiti mothers, Bedouns with
relatives, Bedouns holding registration documents as proof and
Bedouns without documents of proof.
</P>
<P>
Since the last category of Bedouns are believed to be
concealing their original nationalities, they are subject to
deportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980907.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Killed, 8 Injured in Road Accident in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Seven people were killed
and eight others injured in a road accident in Midrand,
Johannesburg, Sunday evening, SABC TV reported.
</P>
<P>
The victims were soccer fans who had just watched a premier
league match in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Six died instantly and another died on the way to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Although the cause of the accident has not been officially
established, it is believed that the driver of the minibus lost
control of the vehicle and veered into a ditch. 
</P>
