<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premiership Untroubled by Murdoch Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Media giant Rupert Murdoch's
planned take-over of Manchester United is unlikely to face strong
opposition from the football authorities, according to English
Premier League chief executive Peter Leaver on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had "no real reaction at all" to Murdoch's
plans.
</P>
<P>
"That is a matter for him," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If he acquires a club which is already a member of another
club, called the FA Premier League, it will remain within that
club.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to take a look at the terms of the offer," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I can't see why there should be an objections."
</P>
<P>
The news that Murdoch may buy the club comes only one week
after Premiership clubs expressed misgivings about the proposed
European Super League.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour discussion last week the clubs - including
Manchester United, Arsenal and Liverpool, who have already been
invited to join the Super League - agreed that all future
discussions on the subject will be conducted through the Premier
League rather than in secret by a few select clubs.
</P>
<P>
British sports minister Tony Banks said Murdoch's plans could
have serious implications for the sport as a whole and he cast
doubt on whether the deal would go through without being handed
to the Office of Fair Trading.
</P>
<P>
"Television is relying more and more on sport to sell
advertising," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If you buy up the biggest football club in the country then
clearly the implications for commercial policy are fairly
profound,"he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
