</P>
<P>
-- The gloves have come off in the federal election campaign as
it moves into a "negative" phase before the main parties' setpiece
policy launches. Labor Sunday night launched advertisements
attacking the government's family credentials, portraying a goods
and services tax as the final blow to families.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- Sydney's water crisis could last another six months even if
no new contamination of Warragamba Dam occurs at that time, Sydney
Water Ltd. has confirmed. If the dam's catchment receives
above-average summer rainfalls, the city may face a string of
boil-water alerts for the next year.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard Sunday said he was in the job for
the long haul, seemingly putting on hold any leadership
aspirations of Treasurer Peter Costello.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- The Coalition is under pressure to amend its tax reform
package to lower rural petrol prices and to match Labor's promises
on industry protection, as the election campaign enters a new
aggressive phase.  
</P>
